9    """ 
10   ``torch.fx.experimental.symbolic_shapes`` provides interfaces for interacting with 
11   our symbolic shapes reasoning system that is used heavily in torch.compile.  Although 
12   this is not generally considered public API, when writing framework code in PyTorch 
13   as well as extensions to PyTorch (e.g., in custom operator implementations), you may 
14   need to make use of these APIs to setup dynamic shapes support appropriately. 
15   """

122          super().__init__(*args)

183  def log_lru_cache_stats(wrapped_f: functools._lru_cache_wrapper[object]) -> None:
184      log.debug(
185          "lru_cache_stats %s: %s",
186          wrapped_f.__name__,  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
187          wrapped_f.cumulative_cache_info(),  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
188      )

191  # Note about Sympy Expr/SympyBoolean/Basic typing: the Sympy hierarchy is
192  #
193  #   Basic
194  #       Expr
195  #       SympyBoolean
196  #           Relational
197  #
198  # Notably, Expr and SympyBoolean are not related.  So use Basic when the
199  # expression could denote int, float OR bool, and otherwise use the more
200  # specific Expr for int/float and SympyBoolean for bool.
201  #
202  # In obscure Meta only situations, sympy.logic.boolalg doesn't exist at runtime.
203  # So make sure only type checker evaluates this alias.
204  # Xref: https://www.internalfb.com/diff/D53324783
205  SympyBoolean: TypeAlias = "sympy.logic.boolalg.Boolean"
206  
207  
208  _T = TypeVar("_T")
209  _SympyT = TypeVar("_SympyT", sympy.Expr, SympyBoolean, sympy.Basic)

212  class SymIntEqByExpr:
213      """ 
214      This is a wrapper around SymInt which has alternative semantics for 
215      equality.  Specifically, instead of erroring or guarding, we 
216      instead will hash/compare equality based on the underlying sympy 
217      expression; e.g., s0 and s1 will always compare as False. 
218   
219      NB: This does NOT do fancy analysis that maybe_evaluate_static does; 
220      we can only reason through equalities that occur because to expressions 
221      canonicalize to the same expression via regular simplification. 
222      """
223  
224      val: Union[torch.SymInt, int]
225  
226      def __init__(self, val: Union[torch.SymInt, int]) -> None:
227          self.val = val
228  
229      def __repr__(self) -> str:
230          return repr(self.val)
231  
232      def _extract(self) -> sympy.Expr:
233          if isinstance(self.val, torch.SymInt):
234              return self.val.node.expr
235          else:
236              return sympy.Integer(self.val)
237  
238      def __eq__(self, other: object) -> bool:
239          assert isinstance(other, SymIntEqByExpr)
240  
241          # int equality fastpath
242          if type(self.val) is int and type(other.val) is int:
243              return self.val == other.val
244  
245          return self._extract() == other._extract()
246  
247      def __hash__(self) -> int:
248          return hash(self._extract())
249  
250  
251  def _nested_int_aware_sort(
252      tup: tuple[IntLikeType, int],
253  ) -> tuple[int, IntLikeType, int]:
254      return (
255          # Order nested ints by their coefficients.
256          # 1 here to order nested ints after non-nested-ints.
257          (1, tup[0].node.nested_int_coeff(), tup[1])
258          if is_nested_int(tup[0])
259          else (0, *tup)
260      )
261

263  # Wrapper on lru_cache that reports statistics at process end
264  def lru_cache(
265      maxsize: Optional[int],
266  ) -> Callable[[Callable[..., _T]], functools._lru_cache_wrapper[_T]]:
267      def inner(f: Callable[..., _T]) -> functools._lru_cache_wrapper[_T]:
268          wrapped_f = functools.lru_cache(maxsize)(f)
269          old_cache_clear = wrapped_f.cache_clear
270          prev_hits = 0
271          prev_misses = 0
272  
273          # TODO: There's a ref-cycle here (wrapped_f -> cumulative_cache_info
274          # -> wrapped_f) but cannot be solved with weakref as wrapped_f is not
275          # weakref'able on some versions of Python
276  
277          def cumulative_cache_info() -> functools._CacheInfo:
278              cur = wrapped_f.cache_info()
279              return functools._CacheInfo(
280                  prev_hits + cur.hits,
281                  prev_misses + cur.misses,
282                  cur.maxsize,
283                  cur.currsize,
284              )
285  
286          def new_cache_clear() -> None:
287              nonlocal prev_hits, prev_misses
288              cur = wrapped_f.cache_info()
289              prev_hits += cur.hits
290              prev_misses += cur.misses
291              old_cache_clear()
292  
293          wrapped_f.cache_clear = new_cache_clear  # type: ignore[attr-defined, method-assign]
294          wrapped_f.cumulative_cache_info = cumulative_cache_info  # type: ignore[attr-defined, method-assign]
295          if log.isEnabledFor(logging.DEBUG):
296              atexit.register(log_lru_cache_stats, wrapped_f)  # type: ignore[arg-type]
297          return wrapped_f
298  
299      return inner

302  # These are modules that contain generic code for interacting with ShapeEnv
303  # which are unlikely to identify a particular interesting guard statement
304  @lru_cache(None)
305  def uninteresting_files() -> set[str]:
306      import torch._compile
307      import torch._dynamo.eval_frame
308      import torch._inductor.sizevars
309      import torch._library.custom_ops
310      import torch._library.fake_impl
311      import torch._logging
312      import torch._subclasses.fake_tensor
313      import torch._subclasses.meta_utils
314  
315      mods = [
316          sys.modules[__name__],
317          torch.fx.experimental.recording,
318          torch.fx.experimental.sym_node,
319          torch.fx.interpreter,
320          torch,
321          torch._compile,
322          torch._dynamo.eval_frame,
323          torch._inductor.sizevars,
324          torch._library.custom_ops,
325          torch._library.fake_impl,
326          torch._subclasses.meta_utils,
327          torch._subclasses.fake_tensor,
328          torch._logging._internal,
329          torch._logging.structured,
330      ]
331      import torch._dynamo.guards
332  
333      return (
334          {inspect.getfile(m) for m in mods}
335          | torch._dynamo.guards.uninteresting_files()
336          | {"<string>"}
337      )

350  
351  def create_contiguous(shape: Sequence[Int]) -> list[Int]:
352      strides: list[Int] = [1]
353      for dim in reversed(shape[:-1]):
354          strides.append(dim * strides[-1])  # type: ignore[operator]
355      return list(reversed(strides))

358  def hint_int(a: Union[torch.SymInt, int], fallback: Optional[int] = None) -> int:
359      """ 
360      Retrieve the hint for an int (based on the underlying real values as observed 
361      at runtime).  If no hint is available (e.g., because data dependent shapes), 
362      if fallback is not None, use that instead (otherwise raise an error). 
363      """
364      if isinstance(a, torch.SymInt):
365          return a.node.require_hint(fallback)
366      assert type(a) is int, a
367      return a

374      if isinstance(a, SymTypes):

376      return True

379  def is_concrete_int(a: IntLikeType) -> bool:
380      """ 
381      Utility to check if underlying object 
382      in SymInt is concrete value. Also returns 
383      true if integer is passed in. 
384   
385      Args: 
386          a (SymInt or int): Object to test if it int 
387      """
388      assert isinstance(a, (SymInt, int))
389  
390      if isinstance(a, int):
391          return True
392  
393      if isinstance(a.node.expr, sympy.core.numbers.Integer):
394          return True
395  
396      return False
397  
398  
399  def is_concrete_float(a: FloatLikeType) -> bool:
400      r"""Utility to check if underlying object 
401      in SymInt is concrete value. Also returns 
402      true if integer is passed in. 
403   
404      Args: 
405          a (SymInt or float): Object to test if it float 
406      """
407      assert isinstance(a, (SymFloat, float))
408  
409      if isinstance(a, float):
410          return True
411  
412      if isinstance(a.node.expr, sympy.core.numbers.Float):
413          return True
414  
415      return False
416  
417  
418  def is_concrete_bool(a: BoolLikeType) -> bool:
419      """ 
420      Utility to check if underlying object 
421      in SymBool is concrete value. Also returns 
422      true if integer is passed in. 
423   
424      Args: 
425          a (SymBool or bool): Object to test if it bool 
426      """
427      assert isinstance(a, (SymBool, bool))
428  
429      if isinstance(a, bool):
430          return True
431  
432      if isinstance(
433          a.node.expr, (sympy.logic.boolalg.BooleanTrue, sympy.logic.boolalg.BooleanFalse)
434      ):
435          return True
436  
437      return False

439  
440  def has_static_value(a: Union[SymBool, SymFloat, SymInt, bool, float, int]) -> bool:
441      """ 
442      User-code friendly utility to check if a value is static or dynamic. 
443      Returns true if given a constant, or a symbolic expression with a fixed value. 
444   
445      Args: 
446          a (Union[SymBool, SymFloat, SymInt, bool, float, int]): Object to test 
447      """
448      assert isinstance(a, BoolLike + FloatLike + IntLike)
449      if (
450          isinstance(a, BoolLike)
451          and is_concrete_bool(a)  # type: ignore[arg-type]
452          or isinstance(a, FloatLike)
453          and is_concrete_float(a)  # type: ignore[arg-type]
454          or isinstance(a, IntLike)
455          and is_concrete_int(a)  # type: ignore[arg-type]
456      ):
457          return True
458  
459      assert isinstance(a, py_sym_types)
460      return a.node.shape_env.bound_sympy(a.node.expr).is_singleton()  # type: ignore[union-attr]
461  
462  
463  def guard_size_oblivious(expr: Union[torch.SymBool, bool]) -> bool:
464      """ 
465      Perform a guard on a symbolic boolean expression in a size oblivious way. 
466      This is typically used when a non-oblivious test would result in a guard 
467      on a data dependent value of which we don't know the value of at compile time. 
468      When a guard is tested this way, we may diverge in behavior from how regular 
469      PyTorch semantics would treat it.  For more information, see 
470      https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/pull/118579 
471      """
472      if isinstance(expr, torch.SymBool):
473          return expr.node.guard_size_oblivious("", 0)
474      else:
475          assert isinstance(expr, bool), expr
476          return expr
477  
478  
479  def check_consistent(new: _T, old: _T) -> None:
480      """ 
481      Test that two "meta" values (typically either Tensor or SymInt) have 
482      the same values, e.g., after retracing.  If we don't understand the 
483      quantities in question, we'll just skip the consistency check. 
484      """
485      # TODO: do boolean equality test too, see
486      # https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/124110
487      scalar_types = (torch.SymInt, torch.SymFloat, int, float)
488  
489      if isinstance(new, torch.Tensor):
490          assert isinstance(old, torch.Tensor)
491          torch._check(
492              old.dim() == new.dim(), lambda: f"{old.shape} != {new.shape} (old != new)"
493          )
494          # Do this manually so that each individual test is irrefutable
495          # (TODO: should be a helper for this, maybe sym_eq?  That
496          # gives us a compound expression and I'm not sure it
497          # simplifies right now)
498          for i, j in zip(old.shape, new.shape):
499              torch._check(i == j, lambda: f"{old.shape} != {new.shape} (old != new)")
500      # NB: bool is subclass of int
501      elif isinstance(new, scalar_types) and not isinstance(new, bool):
502          assert isinstance(old, scalar_types) and not isinstance(old, bool), (
503              f"{old} != {new}"
504          )
505          torch._check(old == new, lambda: f"{old} != {new} (old != new)")
506  
507  
508  def resolve_unbacked_bindings(
509      shape_env: Optional[ShapeEnv],
510      bindings: Optional[dict[sympy.Symbol, pytree.KeyPath]],
511  ) -> Optional[dict[sympy.Symbol, pytree.KeyPath]]:
512      """ 
513      When we do fake tensor prop, we oftentimes will allocate new unbacked symints. 
514      We then run proxy tensor mode, which populates node.meta["unbacked_bindings"] 
515      with these new symints. To ensure consistency we use PropagateUnbackedSymInts 
516      to rename unbacked bindings to their old ones. But all of the node metas are 
517      still using the old bindings from before the renaming. This function helps to 
518      post facto apply any renamings discovered in the PropogateUnbackedSymInts pass. 
519      """
520      if bindings is None:
521          return None
522      assert shape_env is not None
523      return {shape_env.unbacked_renamings.get(k, k): v for k, v in bindings.items()}
524  
525  
526  Result: TypeAlias = Union[torch.Tensor, tuple[torch.Tensor, ...]]
527  
528  
529  def rebind_unbacked(
530      shape_env: Optional[ShapeEnv], n: torch.fx.Node, result: Result
531  ) -> None:
532      """ 
533      Suppose we are retracing a pre-existing FX graph that previously had 
534      fake tensor propagation (and therefore unbacked SymInts).  When we retrace, 
535      we re-propagate fake tensors, which results in new unbacked SymInts. 
536      When this happens, we need to tell the shape environment about the equivalence 
537      of the old and new unbacked SymInts.  Pass us the old torch.fx.Node (which 
538      has the old binding information) and the new result (which we can extract the 
539      new unbacked SymInts out from). 
540      """
541  
542      # Inputs never need rebinding
543      if n.op == "placeholder":
544          return
545  
546      if bindings := resolve_unbacked_bindings(
547          shape_env, n.meta.get("unbacked_bindings")
548      ):
549          assert shape_env is not None
550          for raw_u0, path in bindings.items():
551              u1 = pytree.key_get(result, path)
552              # Sometimes, things were previously unbacked bindings become constants.
553              # There are two situations this can happen.
554              #
555              # First, you might have a runtime assert that causes the
556              # constant-ification.  In this case, the /binding/ itself will
557              # still be an unbacked symbol (because we will only force it
558              # to be a constant later in fake tensor propagation).  In this
559              # case, u1 is a SymInt and we still do all our work as normal.
560              #
561              # But second, it might be that fake tensor propagation DIRECTLY
562              # converted the unbacked SymInt into a constant.  This happens
563              # more rarely, but we have identified two situations it can
564              # validly occur:
565              #
566              # - If you have a tensor_version operator, these are initially
567              #   allocated as unbacked SymInts, but after AOTAutograd they
568              #   get forced specialized to specific values.  In this case,
569              #   there is no reason to do runtime asserts on them, this is
570              #   just a hack to properly keep track of them to start.
571              #
572              # - If you have an item() call on a constant tensor, the result
573              #   of the item() call is constant and we do not need runtime
574              #   asserts on this symbol.  In
575              #   https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/140625 we have a
576              #   case where in the initial trace of the program we are unable
577              #   to determine that torch.tensor is constant, but then
578              #   subsequent passes cause torch.tensor to become a constant and
579              #   then the unbacked symbol goes poof.
580              #
581              # In all of these cases, it is no longer necessary to generate
582              # deferred runtime asserts, since other subsystems (e.g., the
583              # constant-ification pass) ensure that the quantity is now truly
584              # static and cannot change at runtime.  So it's OK to discard
585              # in these situations.
586              #
587              # There is one more hazard (re
588              # https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/141248), the problem
589              # is that you can end up with "dangling" unbacked symbols that
590              # exist in the ShapeEnv but are never bound anywhere.  You might
591              # like an invariant that unbacked symbols never get lost.  But
592              # we do not have this invariant, so do not try to enforce it.
593              if isinstance(u1, int):
594                  log.info(
595                      "rebind_unbacked: discard %s %s %s -> %s",
596                      n.target,
597                      raw_u0,
598                      path,
599                      u1,
600                  )
601                  continue
602  
603              # We only care about rebinding unbacked things
604              if u1.node.hint is not None:
605                  continue
606  
607              raw_u1 = u1.node.expr
608              # Simplify SymBool binding
609              if (
610                  isinstance(raw_u1, sympy.Piecewise)
611                  and len(raw_u1.args) == 2
612                  and (
613                      raw_u1_args0 := cast(
614                          tuple[sympy.Basic, sympy.Basic], raw_u1.args[0]
615                      )
616                  )
617                  and raw_u1_args0[0] == 1
618                  and isinstance(eq := raw_u1_args0[1], sympy.Eq)
619                  and isinstance(new_raw_u1 := eq.lhs, sympy.Symbol)
620                  and shape_env.var_to_range[new_raw_u1].issubset(ValueRanges(0, 1))
621                  and eq.rhs == 1
622                  and cast(tuple[sympy.Basic, sympy.Basic], raw_u1.args[1]) == (0, True)
623              ):
624                  # This is what the pattern match above is testing
625                  repacked = _sympy_cast_symbool_to_symint_guardless(
626                      sympy.Eq(new_raw_u1, 1)
627                  )
628                  assert repacked == raw_u1, f"{repacked} != {raw_u1}"
629                  # Cancel the to_int(to_bool(x)). This is sound because x in
630                  # [0, 1]
631                  raw_u1 = new_raw_u1
632  
633              if not isinstance(raw_u1, sympy.Symbol):
634                  assert not raw_u1.free_symbols, (
635                      f"should have been constant, but got {raw_u1}"
636                  )
637                  continue
638  
639              # The old and new could be the same if you improperly hit the memo
640              # while retracing.  Make sure you updated FakeTensorMode.epoch
641              assert raw_u0 != raw_u1, f"{raw_u0} possible memo disaster"
642              # Reuse the OLD symbol name
643              shape_env._rename_unbacked_to(raw_u1, raw_u0)
644  
645  
646  # NB: You could try to expand this to cover more cases by simply
647  # detecting whenever you have an int output, but this is a bit
648  # dangerous in case someone adds a function that returns an int but is
649  # mutating.  So manually whitelist for now.
650  def is_accessor_node(node: torch.fx.Node) -> bool:
651      """ 
652      Helper function to determine if a node is trying to access 
653      a symbolic integer such as size, stride, offset or item. Currently 
654      primarily only used in a DCE pass to figure out purity. 
655      """
656  
657      # Dynamo only exercised condition
658      if (
659          node.op == "call_method"
660          and isinstance(node.args[0], torch.fx.Node)
661          and isinstance(node.args[0].meta.get("example_value"), torch.Tensor)
662          and node.target in ["size", "stride", "storage_offset", "item"]
663      ):
664          return True
665  
666      if node.op == "call_function" and node.target in [
667          torch.ops.aten.sym_size,
668          torch.ops.aten.sym_size.default,
669          torch.ops.aten.sym_size.int,
670          torch.ops.aten.sym_stride,
671          torch.ops.aten.sym_stride.default,
672          torch.ops.aten.sym_stride.int,
673          torch.ops.aten.sym_storage_offset,
674          torch.ops.aten.sym_storage_offset.default,
675          torch.ops.aten.sym_numel.default,
676      ]:
677          return True
678  
679      return False
680  
681  
682  def canonicalize_bool_expr(expr: _T) -> _T:
683      """ 
684      Canonicalize a boolean expression by transforming it into a lt / le 
685      inequality and moving all the non-constant terms to the rhs. 
686      We canonicalize And / Ors / Not via cnf and then canonicalize their subexpr 
687      recursively 
688      nb. sympy.Rel.canonical is not good enough https://github.com/sympy/sympy/issues/25924 
689   
690      Args: 
691          expr (sympy.Expr): Expression to canonicalize 
692      """
693      # Canonicalise an inequality by transforming it into a lt / le
694      # inequality and moving all the non-constant terms to the rhs
695      # We canonicalise And / Ors / Not via cnf
696      # nb. Relational.canonical in sympy is broken
697      # https://github.com/sympy/sympy/issues/25924
698  
699      if not isinstance(
700          expr, (sympy.Rel, sympy.And, sympy.Or, sympy.Not, sympy.Eq, sympy.Ne)
701      ):
702          return expr
703  
704      if isinstance(expr, (sympy.And, sympy.Or, sympy.Not)):
705          expr = sympy.logic.boolalg.to_cnf(expr)
706      return _canonicalize_bool_expr_impl(expr)  # type: ignore[arg-type, return-value]
707  
708  
709  def _sympy_from_args(
710      cls: type[Union[sympy.Add, sympy.Mul]],
711      args: list[sympy.Expr],
712      sort: bool = True,
713      is_commutative: Optional[bool] = None,
714  ) -> sympy.Expr:
715      """ 
716      Create a sympy expression from a list of arguments, optimizing for performance. 
717   
718      This function creates a sympy Add or Mul expression from a list of arguments 
719      while avoiding expensive operations like flattening. It handles sorting the 
720      arguments appropriately based on the expression type. 
721   
722      Args: 
723          cls: The sympy class to create (Add or Mul) 
724          args: List of sympy expressions to combine 
725          sort: Whether to sort the arguments (default: True) 
726          is_commutative: Whether the operation is commutative (default: None) 
727   
728      Returns: 
729          A sympy expression of type cls combining all arguments 
730   
731      Raises: 
732          ValueError: If cls is not sympy.Add or sympy.Mul 
733      """
734  
735      if not args:
736          return cls.identity  # type: ignore[union-attr]
737  
738      # These args are already in canonical form, so we avoid calling
739      # Add(*args) to avoid expensive Add.flatten operation
740      if sort:
741          if cls is sympy.Add:
742              sort_fn = sympy.core.add._addsort
743          elif cls is sympy.Mul:
744              sort_fn = sympy.core.mul._mulsort
745          else:
746              raise ValueError(f"Unknown cls: {cls}")
747  
748          # we don't support non commutative with sort
749          assert is_commutative is True
750          if args[0].is_Number:
751              rest = args[1:]
752              sort_fn(rest)
753              return cls._from_args([args[0]] + rest, is_commutative=is_commutative)  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
754          else:
755              args = args.copy()
756              sort_fn(args)
757              return cls._from_args(args, is_commutative=is_commutative)  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
758      else:
759          # if the args are already sorted, we create directly
760          return cls._from_args(args, is_commutative=is_commutative)  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
761  
762  
763  def _canonicalize_bool_expr_impl(expr: SympyBoolean) -> SympyBoolean:
764      """ 
765      After canonicalization, we are guaranteed to have eliminated Ge/Gt relations 
766      (rewriting them to Le/Lt, respectively). 
767      """
768      if isinstance(expr, (sympy.And, sympy.Or)):
769          return type(expr)(*map(canonicalize_bool_expr, expr.args))
770  
771      opposite = {sympy.Gt: sympy.Lt, sympy.Ge: sympy.Le}
772      t: Union[type[Any]]
773      if isinstance(expr, tuple(opposite.keys())):
774          rhs = expr.lhs - expr.rhs  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
775          t = opposite[type(expr)]  # type: ignore[index]
776      else:
777          assert isinstance(expr, (sympy.Lt, sympy.Le, sympy.Eq, sympy.Ne))
778          rhs = expr.rhs - expr.lhs
779          t = type(expr)
780  
781      def is_neg(t: sympy.Expr) -> bool:
782          return (t.is_Number and t.is_negative) or (
783              isinstance(t, sympy.Mul) and t.args[0].is_Number and t.args[0].is_negative
784          )
785  
786      lhs = S.Zero
787      rhs = _reduce_to_lowest_terms(rhs)
788      if isinstance(rhs, sympy.Add):
789          pos = []
790          neg = []
791          for term in rhs.args:
792              if is_neg(term):
793                  neg.append(-term)
794              else:
795                  pos.append(term)
796          # these are already sorted
797          rhs = _sympy_from_args(sympy.Add, pos, sort=False, is_commutative=True)
798          # the terms were changed, so needs a sorting
799          lhs = _sympy_from_args(sympy.Add, neg, sort=True, is_commutative=True)
800      elif is_neg(rhs):
801          # lhs == 0
802          lhs, rhs = -rhs, S.Zero
803      # We don't have to evaluate here because lhs, rhs came from a Boolean
804      # and it was already simplified
805      return t(lhs, rhs, evaluate=False)
806  
807  
808  def _reduce_to_lowest_terms(expr: sympy.Expr) -> sympy.Expr:
809      """ 
810      Eliminates any integer factor from a given expression. 
811      E.g., 6x + 4y reduces to 3x + 2y. 
812   
813      Useful when an expression is == or != to 0. 
814      """
815  
816      def integer_coefficient(x: sympy.Expr) -> int:
817          if x.is_Integer:
818              return abs(int(x))
819          elif x.is_Mul:
820              # If one of the args of a Mul is an Integer, it is the
821              # first arg. eg: args(2*x*3*y) == (6, x, y)
822              return abs(int(x.args[0])) if x.args[0].is_Integer else 1  # type: ignore[call-overload]
823          else:
824              return 1
825  
826      def div_by_factor(x: sympy.Expr, factor: int) -> sympy.Expr:
827          if x.is_Integer:
828              return x / factor
829          elif x.is_Mul:
830              if x.args[0] != factor:
831                  args = [x.args[0] / sympy.Integer(factor), *x.args[1:]]
832              else:
833                  # Mul._from_args require a canonical list of args
834                  # so we remove the first arg (x.args[0] / factor) if it was 1
835                  args = list(x.args[1:])
836              return _sympy_from_args(sympy.Mul, args, is_commutative=x.is_commutative)
837          else:
838              raise AssertionError(f"illegal arg to div_by_factor: {x}")
839  
840      if expr.is_Add:
841          atoms = cast(Sequence[sympy.Expr], expr.args)
842          factor = functools.reduce(math.gcd, map(integer_coefficient, atoms))
843          if factor == 1:
844              return expr
845          atoms = [div_by_factor(x, factor) for x in atoms]
846          return _sympy_from_args(
847              sympy.Add, atoms, sort=True, is_commutative=expr.is_commutative
848          )
849      elif expr.is_Integer:
850          return S.One
851      elif expr.is_Mul:
852          return div_by_factor(expr, integer_coefficient(expr))
853      return expr
854  
855  
856  def is_nested_int(s: IntLikeType) -> TypeGuard[SymInt]:
857      return isinstance(s, torch.SymInt) and s.node.is_nested_int()
858  
859  
860  IterateExprsAtom: TypeAlias = Union[
861      SymInt, SymFloat, SymBool, int, float, bool, sympy.Basic, torch.Tensor
862  ]
863  IterateExprs: TypeAlias = Union[IterateExprsAtom, Sequence[IterateExprsAtom]]
864  
865  
866  def _iterate_exprs(val: IterateExprs) -> Iterator[sympy.Basic]:
867      """ 
868      Recursively iterate through a value and yield all sympy expressions contained within it. 
869   
870      This function traverses various data structures (tensors, lists, tuples, etc.) and extracts 
871      any symbolic expressions they contain. It's used for operations like finding free symbols 
872      in complex nested structures. 
873   
874      Args: 
875          val: The value to extract sympy expressions from. Can be a symbolic type (SymInt, SymFloat, SymBool), 
876               a sympy expression, a primitive type (int, float, bool), a container (tuple, list), 
877               a sparse tensor, a regular tensor, None, or a torch.Generator. 
878   
879      Yields: 
880          sympy.Basic: Each sympy expression found in the value. 
881   
882      Raises: 
883          AssertionError: If the value is of an unsupported type. 
884      """
885      if isinstance(val, SymTypes):
886          # This allow applies to the jagged layout NestedTensor case as
887          # nested ints are not symbolic
888          if is_symbolic(val):
889              yield val.node.expr
890      elif isinstance(val, sympy.Basic):
891          yield val
892      elif isinstance(val, (int, float, bool)):
893          pass
894      elif isinstance(val, (tuple, list)):
895          for s in val:
896              yield from _iterate_exprs(s)
897      elif is_sparse_any(val):
898          yield from _iterate_exprs(val.size())
899      elif isinstance(val, torch.Tensor):
900          yield from _iterate_exprs(val.size())
901          yield from _iterate_exprs(val.stride())
902          yield from _iterate_exprs(val.storage_offset())
903      elif val is None:
904          pass
905      # see Note: [Generator arguments in AOTDispatcher]
906      elif isinstance(val, torch.Generator):
907          pass
908      else:
909          raise AssertionError(f"cannot extract sympy expressions from {val} {type(val)}")
910  
911  
912  def free_symbols(val: IterateExprs) -> OrderedSet[sympy.Symbol]:
913      """ 
914      Recursively collect all free symbols from a value. 
915   
916      This function traverses various data structures (tensors, lists, tuples, etc.) and extracts 
917      all sympy symbols contained within them. It's useful for finding all symbolic variables 
918      that a complex nested structure depends on. 
919   
920      Args: 
921          val: The value to extract symbols from. Can be a symbolic type (SymInt, SymFloat, SymBool), 
922               a container (tuple, list), a tensor, or None. 
923   
924      Returns: 
925          OrderedSet[sympy.Symbol]: An ordered set of all free symbols found in the value. 
926      """
927      if val is None:
928          return OrderedSet()
929  
930      itr = _iterate_exprs(val)
931  
932      # we need at least 1 to call union, so we hand code the identity
933      try:
934          first_expr = next(itr)
935      except StopIteration:
936          return OrderedSet()
937  
938      # TODO: Apparently, returning an OrderedSet here breaks
939      # python test/distributed/tensor/test_dtensor_compile.py TestDTensorCompile.test_dtensor_dynamic
940      return first_expr.free_symbols.union(*(e.free_symbols for e in itr))  # type: ignore[return-value]
941  
942  
943  def has_free_symbols(val: IterateExprs) -> bool:
944      """Faster version of bool(free_symbols(val))"""
945      return not all((e.is_number or e.is_Boolean) for e in _iterate_exprs(val))
946  
947  
948  def has_free_unbacked_symbols(x: IterateExprs) -> bool:
949      """Faster version of bool(free_unbacked_symbols(val))"""
950      from sympy.core.traversal import iterargs
951  
952      for s in _iterate_exprs(x):
953          for arg in iterargs(s):
954              if arg.is_Symbol and symbol_is_type(
955                  arg, (SymT.UNBACKED_INT, SymT.UNBACKED_FLOAT)
956              ):
957                  return True
958      return False
959  
960  
961  def free_unbacked_symbols(x: IterateExprs) -> OrderedSet[sympy.Symbol]:
962      """Like free_symbols, but filtered to only report unbacked symbols"""
963  
964      # NB: keep synced with is_unbacked_symint
965      return OrderedSet(
966          s
967          for s in free_symbols(x)
968          if symbol_is_type(s, (SymT.UNBACKED_INT, SymT.UNBACKED_FLOAT))
969      )
970  
971  
972  # WARNING: Don't use this on Dynamo produced graphs, they don't have meta
973  # setup!
974  def is_symbol_binding_fx_node(node: torch.fx.Node) -> Optional[sympy.Symbol]:
975      """ 
976      Check if a given FX node is a symbol binding node. 
977   
978      A symbol binding node is one that has a SymInt value in its meta that contains 
979      a sympy Symbol expression, and is either a placeholder node or contains unbacked symbols. 
980   
981      Args: 
982          node (torch.fx.Node): The FX node to check 
983   
984      Returns: 
985          Optional[sympy.Symbol]: The sympy Symbol if the node is a symbol binding node, None otherwise 
986      """
987      if (
988          "val" in node.meta
989          and isinstance(node.meta["val"], torch.SymInt)
990          and isinstance(node.meta["val"].node.expr, sympy.Symbol)
991          and (
992              node.op == "placeholder"
993              or free_unbacked_symbols(node.meta["val"].node.expr)
994          )
995      ):
996          return node.meta["val"].node.expr
997      return None
998  
999  
1000 def find_symbol_binding_fx_nodes(
1001     graph: torch.fx.Graph,
1002 ) -> dict[sympy.Symbol, torch.fx.Node]:
1003     """ 
1004     Find all nodes in an FX graph that bind sympy Symbols. 
1005  
1006     This function scans through all nodes in the given FX graph and identifies 
1007     nodes that bind sympy Symbols (typically placeholder nodes with SymInt values). 
1008     When multiple nodes bind the same symbol, only the first occurrence is kept. 
1009  
1010     Args: 
1011         graph: The FX graph to search for symbol binding nodes 
1012  
1013     Returns: 
1014         A dictionary mapping from sympy Symbols to their binding FX nodes 
1015     """
1016     r = {}
1017     # NB: Prefer first occurrence of symbol
1018     for node in graph.nodes:
1019         if (s := is_symbol_binding_fx_node(node)) is not None and s not in r:
1020             r[s] = node
1021     return r

1023 
1024 @dataclass(frozen=True)
1025 class Specialization:
1026     """ 
1027     This class is used in multi-graph compilation contexts where we generate 
1028     multiple specialized graphs and dispatch to the appropriate one at runtime. 
1029     This allows us to optimize the trade-off between performance and generality 
1030     by creating specialized versions for common patterns (e.g., x.shape[0] % 16 == 0) 
1031     while maintaining a general fallback. 
1032     """
1033 
1034     source: TensorPropertySource
1035     check_fn: Callable
1036 
1037 
1038 # Analogous to ConvertIntSource
1039 @dataclass(frozen=True)
1040 class ConvertIntKey:
1041     def __str__(self) -> str:
1042         return ".cast_symbool_to_symint_guardless()"
1043 
1044     def get(self, b: bool) -> IntLikeType:
1045         """Get the int value from bool"""
1046         return cast_symbool_to_symint_guardless(b)
1047 
1048 
1049 @dataclass(frozen=True)
1050 class CallMethodKey:
1051     name: str
1052 
1053     def __str__(self) -> str:
1054         return f".{self.name}()"
1055 
1056     def get(self, o: Any) -> Any:
1057         """Call the method on object"""
1058         return getattr(o, self.name)()
1059 
1060 
1061 @dataclass(frozen=True)
1062 class InnerTensorKey:
1063     inner_name: str
1064 
1065     def __str__(self) -> str:
1066         return f".{self.inner_name}"
1067 
1068     def get(self, o: Any) -> Any:
1069         """Get the inner tensor attribute"""
1070         return getattr(o, self.inner_name)
1071 
1072 
1073 @dataclass(frozen=True)
1074 class DivideByKey:
1075     divisor: IntLikeType
1076 
1077     def __str__(self) -> str:
1078         return f".__floordiv__({self.divisor})"
1079 
1080     def get(self, o: int) -> int:
1081         """Divide object by divisor"""
1082         return o // self.divisor
1083 
1084 
1085 def _free_unbacked_symbols_with_path(
1086     a: object,
1087     path: pytree.KeyPath,
1088     real: Optional[object] = None,
1089     shape_env: Optional[ShapeEnv] = None,
1090     pending: Optional[set[sympy.Symbol]] = None,
1091     simplify: bool = False,
1092 ) -> dict[sympy.Symbol, pytree.KeyPath]:
1093     """ 
1094     Recursively traverses a structure to find unbacked symbols and their access paths. 
1095  
1096     This function walks through tensors, lists, tuples, and symbolic values to locate 
1097     unbacked symbols that are in the pending set, and returns a mapping from those 
1098     symbols to their access paths in the structure. 
1099  
1100     Args: 
1101         a: The object to traverse (tensor, list, tuple, SymInt, etc.) 
1102         path: The current path in the object tree 
1103         real: Optional real tensor corresponding to the fake tensor being traversed 
1104         shape_env: Optional ShapeEnv to register unbacked values with 
1105         pending: Set of unbacked symbols to look for (will be modified in-place) 
1106         simplify: Whether to use simplified expressions 
1107  
1108     Returns: 
1109         A dictionary mapping unbacked symbols to their access paths 
1110     """
1111     go = functools.partial(
1112         _free_unbacked_symbols_with_path,
1113         shape_env=shape_env,
1114         pending=pending,
1115         simplify=simplify,
1116     )
1117 
1118     def expr(s: Union[SymInt, SymFloat, SymBool]) -> sympy.Expr:
1119         if simplify:
1120             return s.node.expr
1121         # (When called from compute_unbacked_bindings)
1122         # NB: Intentionally access _expr, not expr, do not want
1123         # simplification!
1124         return s.node._expr
1125 
1126     if pending is None:
1127         pending = set()
1128     r = {}
1129     if isinstance(a, (tuple, list)):
1130         # NB: real is apparently not always a tuple/list here
1131         # python test/inductor/test_torchinductor.py CpuTests.test_index_propagation_nested_indirect_indexing_cpu
1132         for i in range(len(a)):
1133             r.update(
1134                 go(
1135                     a[i],
1136                     path + (pytree.SequenceKey(i),),
1137                     real=real[i] if real is not None else None,  # type: ignore[index]
1138                 )
1139             )
1140     elif is_traceable_wrapper_subclass(a):
1141         # TODO: Determine if this is correct
1142         attrs, _ = a.__tensor_flatten__()
1143         for attr in attrs:
1144             sub = getattr(a, attr)
1145             r.update(go(sub, path + (InnerTensorKey(attr),)))
1146     elif isinstance(a, torch.Tensor):
1147         from torch._subclasses.fake_tensor import FakeTensor
1148 
1149         assert isinstance(a, FakeTensor)
1150         r.update(
1151             go(
1152                 a.size(),
1153                 path + (CallMethodKey("size"),),
1154                 real=a.real_tensor.size() if a.real_tensor is not None else None,
1155             )
1156         )
1157         if a.layout not in [
1158             torch.sparse_csr,
1159             torch.sparse_csc,
1160             torch.sparse_bsr,
1161             torch.sparse_bsc,
1162         ]:
1163             r.update(
1164                 go(
1165                     a.stride(),
1166                     path + (CallMethodKey("stride"),),
1167                     real=a.real_tensor.stride() if a.real_tensor is not None else None,
1168                 )
1169             )
1170         r.update(
1171             go(
1172                 a.storage_offset(),
1173                 path + (CallMethodKey("storage_offset"),),
1174                 real=(
1175                     a.real_tensor.storage_offset()
1176                     if a.real_tensor is not None
1177                     else None
1178                 ),
1179             )
1180         )
1181 
1182     elif (
1183         isinstance(a, (torch.SymInt, torch.SymFloat))
1184         and isinstance(s := expr(a), sympy.Symbol)
1185         and s in pending
1186     ):
1187         r[s] = path
1188         if shape_env and real is not None:
1189             assert isinstance(real, (int, float))
1190             shape_env.set_unbacked_var_to_val(s, real)
1191         pending.remove(s)
1192     # When an unbacked SymInt is perfectly divisible by an integer
1193     # constant, we replace it with the integer constant to improve
1194     # reasoning capabilities.  However, in synthetic examples, it is
1195     # then possible that the factor never is explicitly allocated.
1196     # Fortunately, we can compute it by division.
1197     elif (
1198         isinstance(a, torch.SymInt)
1199         and isinstance(s := expr(a), sympy.Mul)
1200         and len(s.args) == 2
1201         and isinstance(lhs := s.args[0], (sympy.Integer, sympy.Symbol))
1202         and isinstance(rhs := s.args[1], sympy.Symbol)
1203         # support exactly one unbacked for now
1204         and ((rhs in pending) ^ (lhs in pending))
1205         # support constant coefficient or backed symbolic coefficient
1206         and (
1207             isinstance(coeff := lhs if lhs not in pending else rhs, sympy.Integer)
1208             or shape_env
1209             and coeff in shape_env.var_to_val
1210         )
1211     ):
1212 
1213         def _symint_wrap(s: sympy.Symbol) -> SymInt:
1214             return shape_env.create_symintnode(  # type: ignore[union-attr]
1215                 s,
1216                 hint=int(shape_env.var_to_val[s]),  # type: ignore[union-attr]
1217                 source=shape_env.var_to_sources.get(s, [None])[0],  # type: ignore[union-attr]
1218             )
1219 
1220         unbacked = lhs if lhs in pending else rhs
1221         divisor: IntLikeType = (
1222             int(coeff)
1223             if shape_env and isinstance(coeff, sympy.Integer)
1224             else _symint_wrap(coeff)
1225         )
1226         # TODO: DivideByKey needs to test divisibility at runtime!
1227         r[unbacked] = path + (DivideByKey(divisor),)
1228         if real is not None:
1229             assert isinstance(real, int)
1230             val = (
1231                 real // int(coeff)
1232                 if isinstance(coeff, sympy.Integer)
1233                 else CleanDiv(real, coeff)
1234             )
1235             if shape_env:
1236                 shape_env.set_unbacked_var_to_val(unbacked, val)
1237         pending.remove(unbacked)
1238     # The annoyance here arises from the fact that SymBool is
1239     # allocated by allocating a SymInt and then testing if it's equal
1240     # to one.  So you have a complicated binding site logic for this.
1241     elif (
1242         isinstance(a, torch.SymBool)
1243         and isinstance(s := expr(a), sympy.Eq)
1244         # This must match create_unbacked_symbool EXACTLY
1245         and isinstance(s.lhs, sympy.Symbol)
1246         and s.rhs == 1
1247         and s.lhs in pending
1248     ):
1249         r[s.lhs] = path + (ConvertIntKey(),)
1250         if real is not None:
1251             assert type(real) is bool
1252             if shape_env:
1253                 shape_env.set_unbacked_var_to_val(s, int(real))
1254         pending.remove(s.lhs)
1255 
1256     return r
1257 
1258 
1259 def compute_unbacked_bindings(
1260     shape_env: Optional[ShapeEnv],
1261     example_value: object,
1262     old_example_value: Optional[object] = None,
1263     peek: bool = False,
1264 ) -> Optional[dict[sympy.Symbol, pytree.KeyPath]]:
1265     """ 
1266     After having run fake tensor propagation and producing example_value 
1267     result, traverse example_value looking for freshly bound unbacked 
1268     symbols and record their paths for later.  It is an error if 
1269     we have allocated an unbacked SymInt but it cannot be found in 
1270     example_value.  (NB: this means if you have a multi-output 
1271     function, you must call this on the tuple of tensor output, you 
1272     cannot wait!) 
1273  
1274     The peek parameter lets you check out what the bindings are without 
1275     changing the affected list.  This is primarily useful for ensuring 
1276     unbacked_var_to_val is promptly populated when propagate_real_tensors is on. 
1277     """
1278     if shape_env is None:
1279         return None
1280 
1281     fs = shape_env.pending_fresh_unbacked_symbols
1282     pending = set(fs)
1283     if not pending:
1284         return None
1285 
1286     if not peek:
1287         log.info("compute_unbacked_bindings %s", fs)
1288         fs.clear()
1289 
1290     symbol_to_path = _free_unbacked_symbols_with_path(
1291         example_value, (), shape_env=shape_env, pending=pending, simplify=False
1292     )
1293     if not peek and pending:
1294         extra = (
1295             repr((example_value.stride(), example_value.storage_offset()))
1296             if isinstance(example_value, torch.Tensor)
1297             else ""
1298         )
1299         raise PendingUnbackedSymbolNotFound(
1300             f"Pending unbacked symbols {pending} not in returned outputs {example_value} {extra}.\n"
1301             "Did you accidentally call new_dynamic_size() or item() more times "
1302             "than you needed to in your fake implementation?\n"
1303             "For more help, see https://docs.google.com/document/d/1RWrH-3wLEpzR9kCS6gGBNen_-Fs-8PVbWWFE5AcgeWE/edit"
1304         )
1305 
1306     # Why do we have to do some rebinding here?  If the original FX node
1307     # wasn't a binding site because you had a memo hit, but post
1308     # translation you aren't a memo hit anymore, there's now a new binding
1309     # site... but we know (because it's the same FX node) that the value
1310     # is actually the same, they're just not obviously equal anymore.
1311     #
1312     # The logic here is written carefully, because unlike the
1313     # bind_unbacked case, we are not guaranteed to have a symbol for
1314     # old_sym.  If we have a symbol, do regular rename unbacked to; but if
1315     # we don't, we need to specially eliminate the fresh unbacked symbol
1316     # (NB: we are /trusting/ that the memoization is correct, and that we
1317     # don't need to generate a new runtime assert.  This is load bearing,
1318     # as repropagation can happen after we've frozen runtime asserts.)
1319     if old_example_value is not None:
1320         for keypath in symbol_to_path.values():
1321             old_sym = pytree.key_get(old_example_value, keypath)
1322             new_sym = pytree.key_get(example_value, keypath)
1323             if isinstance(new_sym, SymTypes) and isinstance(
1324                 new_s := new_sym.node.expr, sympy.Symbol
1325             ):
1326                 if (
1327                     isinstance(old_sym, SymTypes)
1328                     and (old_s := old_sym.node.expr) != new_s
1329                 ):
1330                     if isinstance(old_s, sympy.Symbol):
1331                         shape_env._rename_unbacked_to(new_s, old_s)
1332                     else:
1333                         shape_env._eliminate_unbacked(new_s, old_s)
1334                 elif not isinstance(old_sym, SymTypes):
1335                     shape_env._eliminate_unbacked(new_s, sympy.sympify(old_sym))
1336 
1337     return symbol_to_path
1338 
1339 
1340 # Note [guard_or_]
1341 # The following two functions are common utilities used while defining unbacked semantics
1342 # of various framework code. Those would be used in situations you prefer to guard and know
1343 # the result of the expression over not guarding, but in case you hit a data dependent error
1344 # you are ok with just returning true or false.
1345 #
1346 # When to use this?
1347 # (1) If you can use a higher level combinator prefer using those instead, they are definitely safe (modulo short-circuiting).
1348 #
1349 # (2) It can be used if the program would behave equivalently if _guard_or returned true or false.
1350 # Many inductor optimizations fall in this bracket for example.
1351 #
1352 # (3) Finally, it's even be OK if the program wouldn't behave equivalently, so long as the
1353 # change is semantics preserving.  It can be semantics preserving if the program errors in more
1354 # cases than it did previously (but otherwise behaves identically), or if it changes some quantity
1355 # in a way that doesn't matter (e.g., strides often fall in this bucket.)
1356 #
1357 # (4) Specialize for the general case and add a runtime assertion that would fail during
1358 #     runtime if the conditions for the general case are not satisfied. Examples for this are;
1359 #      assuming expand/reshape inputs are not -1. or assuming the non-broadcasting path.
1360 #
1361 def _guard_or(a: BoolLikeType, default: bool) -> bool:
1362     """ 
1363     Try to guard a, if data dependent error encountered just return default. 
1364     """
1365     if not isinstance(a, SymBool):
1366         assert isinstance(a, bool)
1367         return a
1368 
1369     # if backed_size_oblivious is True we treat backed as unbacked here.
1370     if torch.fx.experimental._config.backed_size_oblivious:
1371         result = _static_eval_sym_bool(a)
1372         return result if result is not None else default
1373 
1374     shape_env = getattr(a.node, "shape_env", None)
1375 
1376     # xla symnode path.
1377     if shape_env is None:
1378         return guard_bool(a)
1379 
1380     sym_node = a.node
1381     r = sym_node.shape_env.evaluate_sym_node(
1382         sym_node, size_oblivious=False, fallback_value=default
1383     )
1384     return bool(r)
1385 
1386 
1387 def guard_or_false(a: BoolLikeType) -> bool:
1388     """ 
1389     Try to guard a, if data dependent error encountered just return false. 
1390     """
1391     return _guard_or(a, False)
1392 
1393 
1394 def guard_or_true(a: BoolLikeType) -> bool:
1395     """ 
1396     Try to guard a, if data dependent error encountered just return true. 
1397     """
1398     return _guard_or(a, True)
1399 
1400 
1401 def _static_eval_sym_bool(x: SymBool) -> Optional[bool]:
1402     assert isinstance(x, SymBool)
1403     expr = x.node.expr
1404 
1405     try:
1406         # Shape env access is inside the try on purpose. xla symnode does not
1407         # have it on its attributes.
1408         shape_env = x.node.shape_env
1409         simplified = shape_env._maybe_evaluate_static(expr)
1410         if simplified is not None:
1411             return bool(simplified)
1412         else:
1413             return None
1414     except Exception:
1415         log.debug("Could not simplify %s", expr)
1416         return None
1417 
1418 
1419 def statically_known_false(x: BoolLikeType) -> bool:
1420     """ 
1421     Returns True if x can be simplified to a constant and is False. 
1422     If x cannot be evaluated from static, we return False 
1423  
1424     .. note:: 
1425         This function doesn't introduce new guards, so the expression may end 
1426         up evaluating to False at runtime even if this function returns False. 
1427  
1428     Args: 
1429         x (bool, SymBool): The expression to try statically evaluating 
1430     """
1431     if not isinstance(x, SymBool):
1432         assert isinstance(x, bool)
1433         return not x
1434 
1435     result = _static_eval_sym_bool(x)
1436     if result is None:
1437         return False
1438 
1439     return not result
1440 
1441 
1442 def statically_known_true(x: BoolLikeType) -> bool:
1443     """ 
1444     Returns True if x can be simplified to a constant and is true. 
1445  
1446     .. note:: 
1447         This function doesn't introduce new guards, so the expression may end 
1448         up evaluating to true at runtime even if this function returns False. 
1449  
1450     Args: 
1451         x (bool, SymBool): The expression to try statically evaluating 
1452     """
1453     if not isinstance(x, SymBool):
1454         assert isinstance(x, bool)
1455         return x
1456 
1457     result = _static_eval_sym_bool(x)
1458     if result is None:
1459         return False
1460 
1461     return result
1462 
1463 
1464 def sym_and(x: BoolLikeType, *others: BoolLikeType) -> BoolLikeType:
1465     """ 
1466     and, but for symbolic expressions, without bool casting. 
1467     """
1468     if len(others) == 0:
1469         return x
1470     for y in others:
1471         x = operator.and_(x, y)
1472     return x
1473 
1474 
1475 def sym_eq(x: _T, y: _T) -> BoolLikeType:
1476     """ 
1477     Like ==, but when run on list/tuple, it will recursively test equality 
1478     and use sym_and to join the results together, without guarding. 
1479     """
1480     if isinstance(x, (tuple, list)) and isinstance(y, (list, tuple)):
1481         if len(x) != len(y):
1482             return False
1483         return functools.reduce(operator.and_, map(sym_eq, x, y), True)
1484     elif isinstance(x, (int, torch.SymInt)) and isinstance(y, (int, torch.SymInt)):
1485         return x == y
1486     else:
1487         raise AssertionError(f"unexpected sym_eq between {type(x)} {type(y)}")
1488 
1489 
1490 def sym_or(x: BoolLikeType, *others: BoolLikeType) -> BoolLikeType:
1491     """ 
1492     or, but for symbolic expressions, without bool casting. 
1493     """
1494     if len(others) == 0:
1495         return x
1496     for y in others:
1497         x = operator.or_(x, y)
1498     return x
1499 
1500 
1501 def guard_scalar(
1502     a: Union[SymBool, SymInt, SymFloat, int, bool, float],
1503 ) -> Union[bool, int, float]:
1504     """ 
1505     Guard a scalar value, which can be a symbolic or concrete boolean, integer, or float. 
1506  
1507     This function dispatches to the appropriate guard function based on the type of the input. 
1508  
1509     Args: 
1510         a: A symbolic or concrete scalar value (bool, int, or float) 
1511  
1512     Returns: 
1513         The concrete value after guarding 
1514  
1515     Raises: 
1516         AssertionError: If the input is not a recognized scalar type 
1517     """
1518     if isinstance(a, (SymBool, bool)):
1519         return guard_bool(a)
1520     elif isinstance(a, (SymInt, int)):
1521         return guard_int(a)
1522     elif isinstance(a, (SymFloat, float)):
1523         return guard_float(a)
1524     else:
1525         raise AssertionError(f"unrecognized scalar {a}")
1526 
1527 
1528 def _advise_is_size(a: SymInt) -> None:
1529     """ 
1530     Don't use this directly; use torch._check_is_size instead. 
1531  
1532     This is a softer version of _constrain_range_for_size (with min=0, 
1533     max=Inf).  Instead of forcibly constraining a variable (and erroring if we 
1534     failed to constrain it), it will simply advise us that a size is 
1535     constrained in some way.  We will always defer a runtime assert for this 
1536     constraint if we cannot prove it at compile-time, but we we only 
1537     *sometimes* learn useful extra information at compile-time with this 
1538     information.  This is in contrast to constrain_range_for_size, where if 
1539     you don't call that on a fresh unbacked symint, chances are we will choke. 
1540  
1541     TODO: Make Dynamo handle this appropriately if this is seen in Dynamo-ed 
1542     code.  Right now this is only really used in code with AOTAutograd trace 
1543     through, so it is not a big problem that this isn't supported, but in 
1544     principle all of this code should be Dynamo'able too. 
1545  
1546     TODO: I didn't support min/max because I didn't have a use case where this 
1547     actually helped.  In principle we can support it, it just makes the 
1548     implementation below more complicated. 
1549     """
1550 
1551     # This must always succeed, because the sole allowed caller _check_is_size
1552     # was responsible for expect_true'ing this
1553     # This assert triggers expensive sym compute, do not do it until its cheap.
1554     # assert a >= 0
1555 
1556     # NB: it's important not to constrain range for size for *hinted* SymInts,
1557     # because it is not only unsound, it will immediately trip our asserts
1558     # that hints have to be consistent with static analysis!  If you somehow
1559     # have an unbounded SymInt that later constrains to 1, this will be
1560     # inconsistent with the range
1561     if (
1562         isinstance(a, SymInt)
1563         and isinstance(a.node, SymNode)
1564         and isinstance(a.node.expr, sympy.Symbol)
1565         and a.node.shape_env.is_unbacked_symint(a.node.expr)
1566     ):
1567         _constrain_range_for_size(a)
1568 
1569 
1570 def _advise_is_bounded(a: SymInt, upper_bound: IntLikeType) -> None:
1571     if (
1572         isinstance(a, SymInt)
1573         and isinstance(a.node, SymNode)
1574         and isinstance(a.node.expr, sympy.Symbol)
1575         and a.node.shape_env.is_unbacked_symint(a.node.expr)
1576         and isinstance(upper_bound, int)  # TODO: relax
1577     ):
1578         a.node.shape_env._constrain_is_bounded(a.node.expr, upper_bound)
1579 
1580 
1581 def _constrain_range_for_size(
1582     a: SymInt, min: Optional[int] = None, max: Optional[int] = None
1583 ) -> None:
1584     """ 
1585     This function is NOT INTENDED to be used by itself. 
1586     """
1587 
1588     if isinstance(a, (SymFloat, SymBool)):
1589         raise ValueError("Constraining SymFloat/SymBool is nyi")
1590 
1591     assert isinstance(a, SymInt), "can only constrain range for SymInt"
1592     assert isinstance(a.node.expr, sympy.Symbol), f"constraining non-Symbols NYI: {a}"
1593 
1594     a.node.shape_env._constrain_range_for_size(a.node.expr, min, max)
1595 
1596 
1597 # inclusive both ways
1598 def constrain_range(
1599     a: SymInt, *, min: Optional[int], max: Optional[int] = None
1600 ) -> None:
1601     """ 
1602     Applies a constraint that the passed in SymInt must lie between min-max 
1603     inclusive-inclusive, WITHOUT introducing a guard on the SymInt (meaning 
1604     that it can be used on unbacked SymInts).  If min/max are None, we assume 
1605     that the dimension is unbounded in that direction.  Repeated application 
1606     of constrain_range intersects the ranges.  This is a fairly low level API 
1607     that doesn't have a lot of safety guarantees (TODO: provide higher level 
1608     APIs). 
1609  
1610     Currently, we use this API in the following circumstance: when we allocate 
1611     an unbacked SymInt, denoting an integer quantity which is data dependent, 
1612     we ordinarily do not know anything about what values it may take.  This 
1613     means that any sort of guard on it will immediately fail.  However, in 
1614     many cases, we know something about the unbacked SymInt: for example, we 
1615     know that nonzero(x).size(0) must be >= 0.  We use constrain_range to 
1616     narrow the possible range, declaring that negative symbols are impossible. 
1617     This permits to definitely answer True to queries like 'nnz >= 0', even if 
1618     we don't know what the actual (hinted) value of 'nnz' is.  In fact, we 
1619     actually use constrain_range to unsoundly discharge common guards: for an 
1620     unbacked SymInt produced by nonzero, we will also assume that it is not 
1621     equal to 0/1 (even though these are perfectly possible values at runtime), 
1622     because we generally expect graphs that are valid for N=2 to also be valid 
1623     for N=1. 
1624     """
1625     if min is None:
1626         min = -int_oo
1627     if max is None:
1628         max = int_oo
1629 
1630     if max < min:
1631         raise ValueError(
1632             "Maximum value to constrain_as_size can't be less than the specified min value, "
1633             "received min={min} and max={max}"
1634         )
1635 
1636     if isinstance(a, int):
1637         if not (min <= a <= max):
1638             raise ValueError(f"Invalid value {a} for range [{min}:{max}]")
1639         return
1640 
1641     a.node.shape_env._constrain_range(a.node.expr, min, max)
1642 
1643 
1644 def constrain_unify(a: torch.SymInt, b: torch.SymInt) -> None:
1645     """ 
1646     Given two SymInts, constrain them so that they must be equal.  NB: 
1647     this will not work with SymInts that represent nontrivial expressions 
1648     (yet!) 
1649     """
1650     if not isinstance(a, SymInt):
1651         if not isinstance(b, SymInt):
1652             assert a == b
1653             return
1654         else:
1655             shape_env = b.node.shape_env
1656     else:
1657         shape_env = a.node.shape_env
1658 
1659     shape_env._constrain_unify(a, b)
1660 
1661 
1662 # Assume that a boolean is true for the purposes of subsequent symbolic
1663 # reasoning.  This will keep track of corresponding runtime checks to verify
1664 # that the result is upheld: either as a regular guard, or as a special set
1665 # of asserts which are triggered when an unbacked SymInt is allocated.
1666 #
1667 # DO NOT use this function for these cases:
1668 #
1669 #  - This is inappropriate for "branching" conditions (where both
1670 #    true and false result in valid programs).  We will always assume
1671 #    the condition evaluates true, and so it will never be possible
1672 #    to trace the false condition when you use it.  For true branching
1673 #    on unbacked SymInts, you must use torch.cond; if you incorrectly
1674 #    use expect_true in this case, you will make the false branch
1675 #    unreachable (as we will simply assume that only the true branch
1676 #    is ever exercised).
1677 #
1678 #  - This is inappropriate for situations where you know some other system
1679 #    invariant guarantees that this property holds, since you don't
1680 #    really need to insert a runtime check in that case.  Use something
1681 #    like constrain_range in that case.
1682 #
1683 # This API has a hitch.  To avoid having to reimplement error reporting
1684 # capabilities, this function CAN return False.  The invariant is that
1685 # the surrounding code must raise an error when this function returns
1686 # False.  This is quite low level, so we recommend using other functions
1687 # like check() which enforce this in a more intuitive way.
1688 #
1689 # By the way, this name is a nod to the __builtin_expect macro,
1690 # which is used similarly (but unlike __builtin_expect, you MUST fail
1691 # in the unlikely branch.)  (I think expect is a good name; in recent
1692 # versions of C++, this is replaced with [[likely]], which is weaker
1693 # and not accurate for this function!)
1694 def expect_true(a: BoolLikeType, skip: int = 0) -> bool:
1695     if isinstance(a, SymBool):
1696         # TODO: check perf implications of this
1697         frame = inspect.currentframe()
1698         for _ in range(skip + 1):  # always run this loop at least once
1699             if frame is None:
1700                 break
1701             frame = frame.f_back
1702         return a.node.expect_true(
1703             frame.f_code.co_filename if frame else "", frame.f_lineno if frame else 0
1704         )
1705     assert type(a) is bool, a
1706     return a
1707 
1708 
1709 def guard_bool(a: BoolLikeType) -> bool:
1710     if isinstance(a, SymBool):
1711         return a.node.guard_bool("", 0)  # NB: uses Python backtrace
1712     assert type(a) is bool, a
1713     return a
1714 
1715 
1716 def guard_int(a: IntLikeType) -> int:
1717     if isinstance(a, SymInt):
1718         return a.node.guard_int("", 0)  # NB: uses Python backtrace
1719     assert type(a) is int, a
1720     return a
1721 
1722 
1723 def guard_float(a: FloatLikeType) -> float:
1724     if isinstance(a, SymFloat):
1725         return a.node.guard_float("", 0)  # NB: uses Python backtrace
1726     assert isinstance(a, float), a
1727     return a
1728

1730 # Given a GraphModule, return all the FakeTensors for all the placeholders
1731 def fx_placeholder_vals(gm: torch.fx.GraphModule) -> list[object]:
1732     return [n.meta["val"] for n in gm.graph.nodes if n.op == "placeholder"]
1733 
1734 
1735 def fx_placeholder_targets(gm: torch.fx.GraphModule) -> list[str]:
1736     return [n.target for n in gm.graph.nodes if n.op == "placeholder"]
1737 
1738 
1739 # Given a GraphModule and arguments to run it with, evaluate that the guards
1740 # for its associated ShapeEnv are satisfied by the passed arguments.  This
1741 # WILL check for duck sizing.
1742 def eval_guards(
1743     gm: torch.fx.GraphModule, *args: Tensor, ignore_static: bool = True
1744 ) -> bool:
1745     return gm.shape_env.evaluate_guards_for_args(  # type: ignore[operator, union-attr]
1746         fx_placeholder_vals(gm), args, ignore_static=ignore_static
1747     )
1748 
1749 
1750 def bind_symbols(gm: torch.fx.GraphModule, *args: Tensor) -> dict[sympy.Symbol, int]:
1751     return gm.shape_env.bind_symbols(fx_placeholder_vals(gm), args)  # type: ignore[operator, union-attr]

1753 
1754 class DimDynamic(Enum):
1755     """ 
1756     Controls how to perform symbol allocation for a dimension.  It is always 
1757     sound to default this to DYNAMIC, but the policies DUCK and STATIC can 
1758     result in better trace-time and compile-time performance, as they reduce 
1759     the number of allocated symbols and generally make your graph more static. 
1760  
1761     NB: If we notice you've applied a constraint to the dimension, we will 
1762     force it to DYNAMIC for simplicity. 
1763  
1764     DimDynamic is controlled by a variety of higher level UX features. 
1765     Currently: 
1766  
1767     - In eager mode, the default policy is DUCK. 
1768         - The default is changed to STATIC with assume_static_by_default. 
1769         - An individual dim is marked DYNAMIC if you mark_dynamic_dim. 
1770     - In export mode, the default policy is STATIC. 
1771         - An individual dim is marked DYNAMIC if you specify it in 
1772           dynamic_shapes passed to export. 
1773     """
1774 
1775     # Treat the dimension symbolically
1776     DYNAMIC = 0
1777     # Treat the dimension symbolically, but if its hint matches another
1778     # dynamic dimension, unify the two symbols ("duck sizing")
1779     DUCK = 1
1780     # Treat the dimension statically based on its hint
1781     STATIC = 2
1782     # Treat the dimension as a size-like unbacked
1783     SIZE_LIKE_UNBACKED = 3
1784     # Infer the strides from stride. If size is static, strides will be static as well.
1785     INFER_STRIDE = 4
1786     # Like SIZE_LIKE_UNBACKED, but there's a hint
1787     OBLIVIOUS_SIZE = 5
1788 
1789 
1790 # NB: These constraints affect both clients and backends: given some
1791 # constraint C, the client must pass inputs that satisfy the constraint,
1792 # while a backend must not introduce guards BEYOND this constraint.
1793 # For clarity, we document the implications on both sides for both the client
1794 # and the backend.
1795 #
1796 # NB: These constraints are on a *single* dimension.  In principle, we could
1797 # also have multi-dimension constraints, but our guess is that this is not
1798 # actually useful and so we are not supporting it right now.
1799 #
1800 # NB: Strict constraints are typically only suitable for export, as in eager
1801 # a backend like inductor may validly introduce extra, discretionary guards
1802 # to improve performance of code.  A StrictMinMaxConstraint would be brittle
1803 # under future optimizations performed by inductor; we don't guarantee
1804 # eager code with StrictMinMaxConstraint will keep working in the future!
1805 
1806 
1807 @dataclass(frozen=True)
1808 class Constraint:
1809     warn_only: bool
1810 
1811 
1812 @dataclass(frozen=True)
1813 class StrictMinMaxConstraint(Constraint):
1814     """ 
1815     For clients: the size at this dimension must be within 'vr' (which 
1816     specifies a lower and upper bound, inclusive-inclusive) AND it 
1817     must be non-negative and should not be 0 or 1 (but see NB below). 
1818  
1819     For backends: there must not be any guards on this dimension which 
1820     are not implied by the given lower and upper bound.  Regardless of 
1821     the lower bound, the backend can assume the size is non-negative 
1822     and that it is not 0 or 1. 
1823  
1824     An unbounded StrictMinMaxConstraint can be thought of as a strict version 
1825     of "RelaxedUnspecConstraint". 
1826  
1827     NB: Export will often unsoundly assume that a graph works for 0/1, even 
1828     though at trace time we assumed size is not 0 or 1.  The idea is that 
1829     if we produce a graph that works for a range of values, it will be OK 
1830     for N=0/1 too. 
1831     """
1832 
1833     vr: ValueRanges
1834 
1835     def render(self, source: Source) -> str:
1836         """Format the constrain equation"""
1837         # TODO: better printing for -oo and oo
1838         return f"{self.vr.lower} <= {source.name()} <= {self.vr.upper}"
1839 
1840 
1841 @dataclass(frozen=True)
1842 class RelaxedUnspecConstraint(Constraint):
1843     """ 
1844     For clients: no explicit constraint; constraint is whatever is implicitly 
1845     inferred by guards from tracing. 
1846  
1847     For backends: there must exist at least TWO possible values for the 
1848     size at this dimension which satisfy the guards for this dimension. 
1849  
1850     In other words, this constraint helps us distinguish between "we don't 
1851     care if this dimension specializes or not" versus "this dimension must be 
1852     unspecialized."  However, this constraint doesn't say very much about what 
1853     specialization is permitted; for example, if we guard on a size being 
1854     even, this would still be acceptable under an unspec constraint.  This 
1855     makes RelaxedUnspecConstraint useful for eager mode, where your backend compiler 
1856     may add constraints to otherwise dynamic dimensions; we can't assert that 
1857     there are NO guards as this is brittle because compilers should be able to 
1858     add extra constraints.  If you want to assert that there are no guards, 
1859     use StrictMinMaxConstraint with an unbounded ValueRanges. 
1860     """
1861 
1862     def render(self, source: Source) -> str:
1863         return f"RelaxedUnspecConstraint({source.name()})"
1864 
1865 
1866 # NB: None here indicates the client constraint is whatever is implicitly
1867 # inferred by guards from tracing, and that a backend can add whatever guards
1868 # it wants (including fully specializing the value).
1869 DimConstraint = Union[StrictMinMaxConstraint, RelaxedUnspecConstraint, None]
1870 
1871 
1872 @dataclass(frozen=True)
1873 class EqualityConstraint(Constraint):
1874     """ 
1875     Represent and decide various kinds of equality constraints between input sources. 
1876  
1877     A "source pair" is a pair of input sources for dynamic dimensions that 
1878     are specified equal. We represent `source_pairs` in a union-find forest 
1879     so that we can efficiently check whether two such sources are transitively equal. 
1880  
1881     A "derived equality" relates an input source to an expression over a root. 
1882     The root can be another input source, corresponding to some dynamic dimension, 
1883     or a phantom symbol that does not directly represent any dynamic dimension. We 
1884     represent `derived_equalities` involving input sources in a transitively-closed map 
1885     so that we can efficiently check whether an input source is transitively equal to 
1886     a given expression over another input source. 
1887     (NOTE: In contrast, it is easy to decide whether an input source is transitively equal 
1888     to a given expression over a phantom symbol; such expressions are already in canonical 
1889     form and so the problem reduces to symbolic expression equality.) 
1890     """
1891 
1892     source_pairs: list[tuple[Source, Source]]
1893     derived_equalities: list[
1894         tuple[Source, Union[Source, sympy.Symbol], Callable[[sympy.Expr], sympy.Expr]]
1895     ]
1896     phantom_symbols: list[sympy.Symbol]
1897     relaxed_sources: set[Source]
1898 
1899     _parents: dict[Source, Source] = field(init=False)
1900     _defs: dict[Source, sympy.Expr] = field(init=False)
1901 
1902     def __post_init__(self) -> None:
1903         """ 
1904         Pre-processing to answer queries `is_equal` and `is_derived` below. 
1905  
1906         Example: Suppose we are given: 
1907           source_pairs [a = b, b = c] 
1908           derived_equalities [d = c + 1, e = d - 1] 
1909         We first construct a union find with source_pairs: 
1910           _parents = {a: a, b: a, c: a} 
1911         Then we compute canonical symbolic expressions, recursively applying derived_equalities 
1912         until we bottom out: 
1913           _defs = {d: c + 1, e: (c + 1) - 1 aka c} 
1914         """
1915 
1916         # self._parents is a map from input sources to input sources where, conceptually,
1917         # these are directed edges in a union-find forest
1918         _parents: dict[Source, Source] = {}
1919         object.__setattr__(self, "_parents", _parents)
1920         # self._defs is a map from input sources to "canonical" symbolic expressions,
1921         # i.e., unary expressions with symbols that corresponds to regular Dims (i.e.,
1922         # not derived Dims)
1923         _defs: dict[Source, sympy.Expr] = {}
1924         object.__setattr__(self, "_defs", _defs)
1925 
1926         for source1, source2 in self.source_pairs:
1927             # preprocess into a union-find forest
1928             self._union(self._find(source1), self._find(source2))
1929         for source, root, fn in self.derived_equalities:
1930             # preprocess into a transitively-closed map
1931             # NOTE(avik): we reuse the union-find forest for canonicalizing input sources
1932             if isinstance(root, sympy.Symbol):
1933                 self._defs[self._find(source)] = fn(root)
1934             else:
1935                 self._defs[self._find(source)] = fn(self._rewrite(root))
1936 
1937     def _find(self, source: Source) -> Source:
1938         # chase edges to find the root of this equivalence class
1939         if source in self._parents:
1940             return self._find(self._parents[source])
1941         else:
1942             return source
1943 
1944     def _union(self, root1: Source, root2: Source) -> None:
1945         # merge two equivalence classes by adding an edge from one root to the other
1946         if root1 != root2:
1947             self._parents[root1] = root2
1948 
1949     def _rewrite(self, src: Source) -> sympy.Expr:
1950         # always represent the given source by the root of its equivalence class
1951         src = self._find(src)
1952         if src in self._defs:
1953             # simply look up the definition if it exists
1954             # NOTE(avik): This works because definitions are always transitively-closed;
1955             # otherwise we would have to do recursive rewriting.
1956             return self._defs[src]
1957         else:
1958             # otherwise, create a symbol representing the source
1959             return sympy.Symbol(src.name())
1960 
1961     def is_equal(self, source1: Source, source2: Source) -> bool:
1962         return (
1963             # check whether source1 and source2 have the same root
1964             # or are relaxed
1965             (src1 := self._find(source1)) in self.relaxed_sources
1966             or (src2 := self._find(source2)) in self.relaxed_sources
1967             or src1 == src2
1968             # check whether source1 is derived equal to source2
1969             or self.is_derived(source1, source2, lambda x: x)
1970         )
1971 
1972     def is_derived(
1973         self, src: Source, symbol_src: Source, fn: Callable[[sympy.Expr], sympy.Expr]
1974     ) -> bool:
1975         # check whether both src and symbol_src have the same definition
1976         return self._rewrite(src) == fn(self._rewrite(symbol_src))
1977 
1978 
1979 def _assert_symbol_context(symbolic_context: object) -> TypeGuard[SymbolicContext]:
1980     assert isinstance(symbolic_context, SymbolicContext), (
1981         "Invalid symbolic_context object"
1982     )
1983     assert type(symbolic_context) is not SymbolicContext, (
1984         "Illegal usage of symbolic_context ABC"
1985     )
1986     return True
1987 
1988 
1989 def _is_supported_equivalence(expr: sympy.Expr) -> bool:
1990     # Currently supported Dim ops are linear expressions with integer coefficients.
1991     # So check that expr only contains +, *, ints, and a single occurrence of a symbol.
1992     # (See also documentation of dynamic_shapes._DerivedDim.)
1993     if isinstance(expr, (sympy.Add, sympy.Mul)):
1994         if len(expr.args) > 2:
1995             return False
1996         lhs, rhs = expr.args
1997         return (_is_supported_equivalence(lhs) and isinstance(rhs, sympy.Integer)) or (
1998             isinstance(lhs, sympy.Integer) and _is_supported_equivalence(rhs)
1999         )
2000     return isinstance(expr, sympy.Symbol)
2001

2003 def _has_uninterpretable_sympy_function(expr: sympy.Basic) -> bool:
2004     """ 
2005     Add functions that our sympy interpreter can't reify into FX nodes 
2006     """
2007     return expr.has(
2008         torch.utils._sympy.functions.ToFloat,
2009         torch.utils._sympy.functions.TruncToInt,
2010         torch.utils._sympy.functions.CeilToInt,
2011     )

2014 @dataclass(frozen=True)

2022     another version of this that says "use exactly these SymInts, don't

2040 @dataclass(frozen=True)
2041 class StatelessSymbolicContext(Generic[_P1, _T1], SymbolicContext):
2042     """ 
2043     Create symbols in ``create_symbolic_sizes_strides_storage_offset`` via 
2044     a symbolic_context determination as given by ``DimDynamic`` and ``DimConstraint``. 
2045     This will cause fresh symbols to be allocated 
2046     """
2047 
2048     dynamic_sizes: DimList[DimDynamic]
2049     dynamic_strides: DimList[DimDynamic] = None  # type: ignore[assignment]
2050     constraint_sizes: DimList[DimConstraint] = None  # type: ignore[assignment]
2051     constraint_strides: DimList[DimConstraint] = None  # type: ignore[assignment]
2052     specialize_on: Optional[list[list[Callable[_P1, _T1]]]] = None
2053     # If the tensor is a view, this should be populated for the base. It contains
2054     # information on how to allocate symbols when recursively fakeifying the base
2055     # during view fake-ification.
2056     view_base_context: Optional[SymbolicContext] = None
2057     # TODO: add storage offset and stride symbolic_context
