3555 class ShapeEnv:
3556     # This is a wrapper over the actual __init__ function.
3557     #
3558     # Where to add a new constructor parameter to ShapeEnv?
3559     # =====================================================
3560     # This __init__ function should be used only for parameters related to event recording.
3561     # These are parameters that we don't wish to pass down the road to new ShapeEnv instances
3562     # created from replaying events.
3563     #
3564     # If you wish to add a parameter to the constructor of ShapeEnv, unrelated to event
3565     # recording, do so in the _init function.
3566     def __init__(
3567         self,
3568         *,
3569         should_record_events: Optional[bool] = None,
3570         tracked_fakes: Optional[list[Any]] = None,
3571         **kwargs: Any,
3572     ) -> None:
3573         self._init(**kwargs)
3574 
3575         # Disable event recording when replaying.
3576         kwargs["should_record_events"] = False
3577 
3578         from torch.fx.experimental.validator import translation_validation_enabled
3579 
3580         self._translation_validation_enabled = translation_validation_enabled()
3581 
3582         # If not specified, enable event recording if both:
3583         #   - Translation validation is on
3584         #   - Translation validation bisection is not disabled
3585         self.should_record_events = (
3586             should_record_events
3587             if should_record_events is not None
3588             else (
3589                 self._translation_validation_enabled
3590                 and not config.translation_validation_no_bisect
3591             )
3592         )
3593 
3594         # Enable event recording check if both:
3595         #   - It should record events
3596         #   - The recording check is enabled
3597         self.check_recorded_events = (
3598             self.should_record_events and config.check_shape_env_recorded_events
3599         )
3600 
3601         # This will make sure we only record the top-level function call.
3602         self.is_recording = False
3603         # Keep track of the list of tracked fakes.
3604         self.tracked_fakes = tracked_fakes
3605         # List of events for reconstructing ShapeEnv at arbitrary points in time.
3606         self.events: list[ShapeEnvEvent] = (
3607             [ShapeEnvEvent(ShapeEnv, kwargs=kwargs)]
3608             if self.should_record_events
3609             else []
3610         )
3611 
3612         # FakeTensor per-ShapeEnv operation cache. This is used for caching
3613         # operations that contain symbolic shapes which have guards on the
3614         # ShapeEnv (so are ShapeEnv-dependent).
3615         #
3616         # NOTE: It's important that SymNodes in this cache have their ShapeEnv
3617         # stripped otherwise you end up with cycles which can only be cleaned
3618         # with the GC.
3619         self.fake_tensor_cache: dict[
3620             torch._subclasses.fake_tensor._DispatchCacheKey,
3621             torch._subclasses.fake_tensor._DispatchCacheEntry,
3622         ] = {}
3623 
3624     # Pro-tip: if you add new field to ShapeEnv, this affects some accept
3625     # tests.  Accept their output with:
3626     #
3627     #   EXPECTTEST_ACCEPT=1 python test/dynamo/test_dynamic_shapes.py -k test_shape_env_equal
3628     #
3629     def _init(
3630         self,
3631         *,
3632         allow_scalar_outputs: bool = True,
3633         allow_dynamic_output_shape_ops: bool = True,
3634         # NB: These are legacy configuration that help us make good choices
3635         # when the constraint/dynamic dims are not explicitly passed to us.
3636         # Ideally we will fix all call sites to be explicit and not have
3637         # implicit choices, but this apparently was pretty involved.
3638         assume_static_by_default: bool = False,
3639         # Note - On 0/1 specialization
3640         #
3641         # The following options affect decisions we make about eager
3642         # specialization.  Disabling them will increase trace time (as we do
3643         # more symbolic reasoning) and can also harm the quality of generated
3644         # code (because inductor may not be able to specialize for bounds
3645         # being equal--although if we later respecialize because of a guard,
3646         # your code may be just as good as it was before.)
3647         #
3648         # When True, eagerly specialize input sizes which have 0/1.
3649         specialize_zero_one: bool = True,
3650         # When True, assume input sizes which have the same size are
3651         # symbolically equal.
3652         duck_shape: Optional[bool] = None,
3653         # For debugging
3654         co_fields: Optional[dict[str, str]] = None,
3655         # When True, whenever safe, we will generate a deferred runtime assert
3656         # instead of a guard whenever we know that an expression must be True,
3657         # otherwise it would be an error, even for backed SymInts (where we
3658         # could ostensibly unconditionally generate guards).  This is useful
3659         # for export, where preventing "error checking" sizes from showing up
3660         # in guards is helpful, since these guards in some sense are overly
3661         # pedantic.  See also https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/121749
3662         prefer_deferred_runtime_asserts_over_guards: bool = False,
3663         # When True, does not emit or raise constraint violation errors on
3664         # implicit guards generated by ops, and defers to runtime assertions
3665         # in the graph instead. For export.
3666         allow_complex_guards_as_runtime_asserts: bool = False,
3667         # XXX Add any new settings that could affect FakeTensor evaluation
3668         # to: torch._subclasses.fake_tensor._ShapeEnvSettings
3669         trace_asserts: bool = False,
3670     ) -> None:
3671         if duck_shape is None:
3672             duck_shape = config.use_duck_shape
3673 
3674         self.settings = ShapeEnvSettings(
3675             # Not directly used by ShapeEnv; indirectly used by FakeTensor
3676             allow_scalar_outputs=allow_scalar_outputs,
3677             allow_dynamic_output_shape_ops=allow_dynamic_output_shape_ops,
3678             # End
3679             assume_static_by_default=assume_static_by_default,
3680             specialize_zero_one=specialize_zero_one,
3681             duck_shape=duck_shape,
3682             prefer_deferred_runtime_asserts_over_guards=prefer_deferred_runtime_asserts_over_guards,
3683             allow_complex_guards_as_runtime_asserts=allow_complex_guards_as_runtime_asserts,
3684             trace_asserts=trace_asserts,
3685         )
3686 
3687         self.guards: list[ShapeGuard] = []
3688         self.axioms: dict[sympy.Expr, sympy.Expr] = {}
3689 
3690         # A set of ids that have already been allocated. This is used
3691         # for when we allocate symbol ids using the hash of the source
3692         # names to ensure we don't have collisions via linear probing
3693         self.unique_ids: set[int] = set()
3694         # Maps symbolic ints to their original concrete values
3695         # Currently populated from tensors
3696         self.var_to_val: dict[sympy.Symbol, sympy.Integer] = {}
3697         # Like var_to_val, but only set when propagate_real_tensors is on.
3698         # Used as last resort to avoid GuardOnDataDependent error
3699         self.unbacked_var_to_val: dict[sympy.Symbol, sympy.Integer] = {}
3700         # Like above, but used exclusively for OBLIVIOUS_SIZE.  These
3701         # potentially could be put together but I am not sure, writing out
3702         # the logic individually before abstracting.
3703         self.oblivious_var_to_val: dict[sympy.Symbol, sympy.Integer] = {}
3704         # Maps symbolic ints to their min/max range.  These ranges
3705         # are conservative: the int MUST fall in the range, but the
3706         # range may contain ints which may not actually appear in
3707         # practice
3708         self.var_to_range: dict[sympy.Symbol, ValueRanges] = {}
3709         self.var_to_range_sloc: dict[sympy.Symbol, ValueRangesSLoc] = {}
3710         self.source_name_to_debug_name: dict[str, str] = {}
3711         self.var_to_sources: dict[sympy.Symbol, list[Source]] = {}
3712         self.var_to_stack: dict[sympy.Symbol, CapturedTraceback] = {}
3713         # Maps a source to the *original* symbol that was assigned to it
3714         self.source_to_var: dict[str, sympy.Symbol] = {}
3715         # Maps from sympy ints to expressions representing them
3716         # Populated from equality guards (i.e. a.shape[0] == b.shape[0])
3717         self.replacements: dict[sympy.Symbol, sympy.Expr] = {}
3718         # The sloc of the guard that triggered this replacement to be added
3719         self.replacements_slocs: dict[sympy.Symbol, SLoc] = {}
3720         self.unbacked_renamings: dict[sympy.Symbol, sympy.Symbol] = {}
3721         # Set holds a % b expressions that evaluate to 0.
3722         self.divisible: set[sympy.Expr] = set()
3723         # Set that holds "size-like" symbols.  When we perform
3724         # "size-oblivious" tests, these can be assumed to be >= 2.
3725         self.size_like: set[sympy.Symbol] = set()
3726         # Duck-shaping says that if two input tensors have the same size,
3727         # they get assigned the same symbolic variable
3728         self.val_to_var: dict[int, sympy.Symbol] = {}
3729         self.unbacked_symfloat_counter = itertools.count()
3730         self.unbacked_symint_counter = itertools.count()
3731         # Similar to guards, but these MUST evaluate to true and can
3732         # only be evaluated at runtime midway through (i.e., they always
3733         # involve unbacked symints)
3734         #
3735         # For efficiency reasons, we index in the following way.  Suppose you have
3736         # a runtime assert i0 + i1 <= s1.  We pick the most recently allocated
3737         # symbol in the source expression and add the assert to the list for
3738         # that symbol e.g., {i1: [i0 + i1 <= s1]}.
3739         #
3740         # We access the runtime asserts in two situations:
3741         #
3742         #   - When we are guarding on an expression, we will attempt to
3743         #     statically evaluate it, in case the unbacked SymInts can
3744         #     simplify away.  If we have a runtime assert, we may be able
3745         #     to discharge the guard entirely.  We only need to attempt
3746         #     runtime asserts that mention freevars of the expression in
3747         #     question.
3748         #
3749         #   - When we are performing codegen (in Inductor for eager, or
3750         #     when finalizing the export FX graph), we need to know what
3751         #     extra runtime asserts to insert.  Whenever an unbacked
3752         #     SymInt comes into scope, all runtime asserts involving it
3753         #     become eligible for insertion (so long as all of their other
3754         #     free unbacked symbols are also in scope).  We technically
3755         #     can handle any choice of key by kicking inexpressible asserts
3756         #     to the next unbacked symbol to wait on, but if we choose the
3757         #     latest key, an assert will only show up at the moment when
3758         #     we can actually codegen it.
3759         self.deferred_runtime_asserts: dict[
3760             Optional[sympy.Symbol], list[RuntimeAssert]
3761         ] = {}
3762         # This exists so we can efficiently invalidate the cache (it's used as
3763         # part of the cache key); otherwise we'd have to iterate through
3764         # deferred_runtime_asserts to compute its length
3765         self.num_deferred_runtime_asserts = 0
3766         self.log = log
3767         self.log.info("create_env")
3768         self.frozen = False
3769         self.runtime_asserts_frozen = False
3770         self.dim_constraints: Optional[DimConstraints] = None
3771         self.counter: Counter[str] = collections.Counter()
3772         # Mapping from sympy.Symbol to the number of guards which mention this
3773         # symbol
3774         self.symbol_guard_counter: Counter[sympy.Symbol] = collections.Counter()
3775         # A selection of important fields on co_field; solely used for
3776         # signpost_event
3777         self.co_fields = co_fields if co_fields else {}
3778 
3779         # Whenever we allocate a fresh unbacked Symbol, we add it to this
3780         # pending list.  Unbacked symbol allocation can occur at unpredictable
3781         # points during meta tensor propagation, but at some point, we
3782         # have to know what the binding site for an unbacked symbol is, and
3783         # this is computed when we actually place the node in the graph. The
3784         # important thing is that we always actually handle every unaccounted
3785         # for unbacked symbol, so this list helps us keep track of them and
3786         # then make sure they are all accounted for.
3787         #
3788         # We could potentially give rise to errors earlier by lexically
3789         # scoping when we do propagation, and only allowing unbacked symbols
3790         # to be allocated at this point in time.  However this is inconvenient
3791         # to do in Dynamo, because fake tensor propagation is far from when we
3792         # analyze binding sites (set_example_value), so we do it in a more
3793         # mutatey way.
3794         #
3795         # NB: fresh unbacked symbols NEVER get substitutions applied to them,
3796         # they are binding sites!
3797         self.pending_fresh_unbacked_symbols: list[sympy.Symbol] = []
3798 
3799         # Version counter used to invalidate cached values
3800         self._prev_cache_key = self._get_key()
3801         self._version_counter = 0
3802 
3803         # Each time divisible is changed this should be set to True, this is set in _update_version_counter.
3804         self._resimplify_floor_div_axioms = True
3805 
3806         # Cache for FX nodes.
3807         # Maps an already built node a tuple of:
3808         #   1. node's target
3809         #   2. list of arguments
3810         # This drastically reduces the size of the FX graph, avoiding
3811         # duplicated nodes.
3812         self.fx_node_cache: dict[tuple[Callable, tuple[Any, ...]], torch.fx.Node] = {}
3813         self.source_to_symbol: dict[str, sympy.Symbol] = {}
3814 
3815         # Suppose you want to replace an unbacked symbol with another
3816         # unbacked symbol.  This is error prone because you can cause
3817         # references to unbacked symbols to time travel backwards.  E.g.,
3818         #
3819         # u1 = x.item()
3820         # ... use of u1 ...
3821         # u2 = y.item()
3822         # u3 = z.item()
3823         # torch._check(u1 == u2 + u3)
3824         #
3825         # If you replace u1 with u2 + u3, then the use of u1 now
3826         # references u2 and u3 prior to them actually being bound at
3827         # runtime.
3828         #
3829         # To control for this, we track the order unbacked symbols
3830         # were allocated, and only allow substitutions if they respect
3831         # the dependency from this order; an unbacked symbol can only
3832         # be substituted with unbacked symbols that come before it in the
3833         # order.
3834         #
3835         # This also imposes an ordering on the unbacked symbol binding
3836         # sites themselves: you are not allowed to reorder unbacked symbol
3837         # bindings.  At the moment, this is not tracked, but we potentially
3838         # could track this at the IR level using a higher order operator
3839         # with something like effect token tracking.
3840         self.unbacked_alloc_order: dict[sympy.Symbol, int] = {}
3841 
3842         self.user_specialization_stacks: dict[Source, traceback.StackSummary] = {}
3843         self.framework_specialization_stacks: dict[Source, traceback.StackSummary] = {}
3844 
3845         self.trace_asserts = trace_asserts
3846 
3847         self.specializations: OrderedSet[Specialization] = OrderedSet()
3848 
3849         from torch.fx.experimental.validator import translation_validation_enabled
3850 
3851         self._translation_validation_enabled = translation_validation_enabled()
3852 
3853         if self._translation_validation_enabled:
3854             from torch.fx.experimental.validator import TranslationValidator
3855 
3856             self.validator = TranslationValidator()
3857             self.graph = torch.fx.Graph()
3858             # Create an output graph and start inserting before that.
3859             # This is needed when 'deepcopy'-ing this object.
3860             self.graph.inserting_before(self.graph.output(None))
3861 
3862             # Mapping of each node name to the node itself.
3863             #
3864             # This is useful for matching an FX node from a recorded ShapeEnv.graph
3865             # to the FX node of the ShapeEnv we are running the event on.
3866             #
3867             # Whenever you add a node to self.graph, you must add a mapping to this
3868             # variable. Otherwise, the built FX graph on the replayed ShapeEnv will
3869             # not be valid.
3870             self.name_to_node: dict[str, torch.fx.Node] = {}

3900     @contextmanager
3901     def patch_source_specialization(
3902         self, source: Source, check_fn: Callable[[sympy.Symbol], sympy.Expr]
3903     ) -> Iterator[None]:
3904         """ 
3905         Temporarily add symbol-level axioms to the ShapeEnv. This is useful when you want to "fork" 
3906         and have parallel universes of ShapeEnvs. For example, we use this when doing multi-graph 
3907         compile so we can support various graphs with varying levels of specializations. 
3908  
3909         This context manager allows for temporarily adding constraints to the shape environment 
3910         based on a specialization function applied to a symbol associated with a source. 
3911  
3912         Args: 
3913             source: The source of the symbol to specialize 
3914             check_fn: A function that takes a sympy Symbol and returns a sympy expression 
3915                      representing a constraint/specialization to be applied 
3916         """
3917         name = source.name()
3918         sym = self.source_to_var[name]
3919         expr = check_fn(SymInt(SymNode(sym, self, int, None))).node._expr
3920         new_axioms = dict(self.get_implications(self.simplify(expr)))
3921         added_replacements = {}
3922 
3923         for axiom in new_axioms:
3924             if (
3925                 isinstance(axiom, sympy.Eq)
3926                 and isinstance(axiom.lhs, sympy.Symbol)
3927                 and isinstance(axiom.rhs, sympy.Integer)
3928                 and axiom.lhs not in self.replacements
3929             ):
3930                 self.replacements[axiom.lhs] = axiom.rhs
3931                 added_replacements[axiom.lhs] = axiom.rhs
3932         self.axioms.update(new_axioms)
3933 
3934         # We need to freeze the ShapeEnv becuase any additional modification of
3935         # the ShapeEnv will cause unsoundness for subsequent specialization calls.
3936         self.frozen = True
3937         try:
3938             yield
3939         finally:
3940             for k in new_axioms:
3941                 self.axioms.pop(k, None)
3942             for k in added_replacements:
3943                 self.replacements.pop(k, None)
3944             self.frozen = False
3945 
3946     def check_equal(self, other: ShapeEnv) -> None:
3947         """Compare another ShapeEnv for equivalence"""
3948         # ShapeEnv fields that are not relevant for the outcome of
3949         # ShapeEnv.produce_guards call:
3950         #   - Debugging variables
3951         #   - Translation validation related variables
3952         #   - Events recording related variables
3953         non_state_variable_names = (
3954             "counter",
3955             "log",
3956             "var_to_stack",
3957             "fx_node_cache",
3958             "graph",
3959             "validator",
3960             "check_recorded_events",
3961             "should_record_events",
3962             "is_recording",
3963             "tracked_fakes",
3964             "events",
3965             "source_name_to_debug_name",
3966             "_prev_cache_key",
3967             "_version_counter",
3968             "dim_constraints",
3969             # source locations are OK to diverge
3970             "var_to_range_sloc",
3971             "replacements_slocs",
3972             "_resimplify_floor_div_axioms",
3973             "_expr_sym_node_id",
3974             "user_specialization_stacks",
3975             "framework_specialization_stacks",
3976         )
3977 
3978         # Mapping of the value of each to-be-compared field into the values that
3979         # should actually be compared.
3980         #
3981         # You should modify this if, for example, the field that holds state and
3982         # debugging information. e.g. ShapeGuard holds the actual guard (sympy.Expr)
3983         # and the stack when it was added to the set of guards. In order to compare
3984         # it, we throw away the stack information.
3985         def map_value(key: str, value: Any) -> Any:
3986             if key in ("unbacked_symfloat_counter", "unbacked_symint_counter"):
3987                 from copy import copy
3988 
3989                 # For itertools.count(), we compare the next integer returned
3990                 # by the count iterators. Not that we need to copy the iterator
3991                 # first. Otherwise we are mutating the object.
3992                 return next(copy(value))
3993             elif key == "guards":
3994                 # Transform the list of ShapeGuard into a list of expressions.
3995                 return [g.expr for g in value]
3996             elif key == "deferred_runtime_asserts":
3997                 # Transform the list of RuntimeAsserts into a list of expressions.
3998                 return {s: [ra.expr for ra in ras] for s, ras in value.items()}
3999             elif key == "name_to_node":
4000                 # Compare just the set of keys is the same.
4001                 return set(value.keys())
4002             elif key in (
4003                 "symbol_guard_counter",
4004                 "pending_fresh_unbacked_symbols",
4005                 "fake_tensor_cache",
4006             ):
4007                 # Skip this for comparisons
4008                 return None
4009             return value
4010 
4011         shape_env_check_state_equal(self, other, non_state_variable_names, map_value)
4012 
4013     def _snapshot_tracked_fakes(self) -> Optional[list[Any]]:
4014         if self.tracked_fakes is None:
4015             return None
4016 
4017         from torch._dynamo.variables.builder import TrackedFake
4018 
4019         def maybe_transform_fake(fake: TrackedFake) -> TrackedFake:
4020             inner_fake = (
4021                 fake.fake
4022                 if isinstance(fake.fake, (torch.SymInt, torch.SymFloat))
4023                 else FakeTensorMeta.from_fake(fake.fake)
4024             )
4025             # Even though TrackedFake accepts either a Union[SymInt, FakeTensor], here we give it a
4026             # FakeTensorMeta for two reasons:
4027             #   1. this is all the information we need when recording ShapeEnvEvents.
4028             #   2. it works even if each TrackedFake changes its metadata.
4029             return TrackedFake(inner_fake, fake.source, fake.symbolic_context)  # type: ignore[arg-type]
4030 
4031         return [maybe_transform_fake(fake) for fake in self.tracked_fakes]
4032 
4033     def _last_event_index(self) -> int:
4034         return len(self.events) - 1
4035 
4036     @contextmanager
4037     def _recording(self) -> Iterator[None]:
4038         self.is_recording = True
4039         try:
4040             yield
4041         finally:
4042             self.is_recording = False

4044     @record_shapeenv_event()
4045     def _eliminate_unbacked(self, orig_s: sympy.Symbol, new_s: sympy.Expr) -> None:
4046         self._set_replacement(orig_s, new_s, "eliminate_unbacked")
4047 
4048     @record_shapeenv_event()
4049     def set_unbacked_var_to_val(self, k: sympy.Symbol, v: int) -> None:
4050         """Used only when propagate_real_tensors; registers a value for an 
4051         unbacked symbol, which can be used last resort to resolve hints."""
4052         log.info("set_unbacked_var_to_val %s = %s", k, v)
4053         self.unbacked_var_to_val[k] = sympy.sympify(v)
4054 
4055     # Unlike set_replacement, this records a shapeenv event
4056     @record_shapeenv_event()
4057     def _rename_unbacked_to(self, orig_s: sympy.Symbol, new_s: sympy.Symbol) -> None:
4058         assert isinstance(orig_s, sympy.Symbol), orig_s
4059         assert isinstance(new_s, sympy.Symbol), new_s
4060         assert free_unbacked_symbols(new_s), new_s
4061         assert free_unbacked_symbols(orig_s), orig_s
4062         dest = self.replacements.get(orig_s)
4063         if dest is not None:
4064             assert not free_unbacked_symbols(dest), f"{orig_s} -> {dest}"
4065         self._set_replacement(orig_s, new_s, "rename_unbacked_to")
4066         self.unbacked_renamings[orig_s] = new_s
4067         if dest is not None:
4068             self._set_replacement(new_s, dest, "rename_unbacked_to_dest")
4069 
4070     @record_shapeenv_event()
4071     def _constrain_is_bounded(self, a: sympy.Symbol, upper_bound: int) -> None:
4072         # TODO: Do something nontrivial when upper_bound is expression
4073         pass

4075     @record_shapeenv_event()
4076     def _constrain_range_for_size(
4077         self, a: sympy.Symbol, min: Optional[int] = None, max: Optional[int] = None
4078     ) -> None:
4079         if min is None:
4080             min = 0
4081         if max is None:
4082             max = int_oo
4083 
4084         if max < min:
4085             raise ValueError(
4086                 "Maximum value to constrain_as_size can't be less than the specified min value, "
4087                 "received min={min} and max={max}"
4088             )
4089 
4090         self.constrain_symbol_range(
4091             a,
4092             compiler_min=min,
4093             compiler_max=max,
4094         )
4095         self.size_like.add(a)
4096 
4097     @record_shapeenv_event()
4098     def _constrain_range(self, a: sympy.Expr, min: int, max: int) -> None:
4099         if isinstance(a, sympy.Integer):
4100             if not (min <= int(a) <= max):
4101                 raise ValueRangeError(f"Invalid value {int(a)} for range [{min}:{max}]")
4102             return
4103 
4104         # TODO: Shouldn't we install a guard if the symbol is backed?  Or is the
4105         # semantics that this is an "unchecked" assert (but it this actually
4106         # something useful?  Might be better to restrict only for unbacked
4107         # SymInt).
4108         if isinstance(a, sympy.Symbol):
4109             self.constrain_symbol_range(
4110                 a,
4111                 compiler_min=min,
4112                 compiler_max=max,
4113             )
4114 
4115     @record_shapeenv_event()
4116     def _constrain_unify(self, a: SymInt, b: SymInt) -> None:
4117         """ 
4118         Given two SymInts, constrain them so that they must be equal.  NB: 
4119         this will not work with SymInts that represent nontrivial expressions 
4120         (yet!) 
4121         """
4122         # TODO: this does not install a deferred runtime assert yet
4123 
4124         # TODO: Maybe dedupe this with _maybe_guard_rel?
4125         # Update Feb 2024: this is extra important to do, this doesn't handle
4126         # unbacked replacements properly nor does it generate deferred runtime
4127         # asserts
4128         if not isinstance(a, SymInt):
4129             if not isinstance(b, SymInt):
4130                 assert a == b
4131             else:
4132                 assert isinstance(b.node.expr, sympy.Symbol), (
4133                     "constraining non-Symbols NYI"
4134                 )
4135                 assert b.node.shape_env is self
4136                 self.replacements[b.node.expr] = sympy.Integer(a)
4137         else:
4138             # TODO: Actually, we can support this as long as one of them is a symbol.
4139             # NB: We can't actually do "unification" as our operators are not
4140             # injective
4141             assert isinstance(a.node.expr, sympy.Symbol), "constraining non-Symbols NYI"
4142             assert a.node.shape_env is self
4143             if not isinstance(b, SymInt):
4144                 self.replacements[a.node.expr] = sympy.Integer(b)
4145             else:
4146                 assert a.node.shape_env is b.node.shape_env
4147                 assert isinstance(b.node.expr, sympy.Symbol), (
4148                     "constraining non-Symbols NYI"
4149                 )
4150                 new_var = self._find(a.node.expr)
4151                 self.replacements[b.node.expr] = new_var
4152 
4153     def _ignore_fresh_unbacked_symbols_tls(self) -> bool:
4154         return getattr(TLS, "ignore_fresh_unbacked_symbols", False)
4155 
4156     @record_shapeenv_event()
4157     def _ignore_fresh_unbacked_symbols_set(self, b: bool) -> bool:
4158         prev = self._ignore_fresh_unbacked_symbols_tls()
4159         TLS.ignore_fresh_unbacked_symbols = b
4160         return prev
4161 
4162     @contextmanager
4163     def ignore_fresh_unbacked_symbols(self) -> Iterator[None]:
4164         """ 
4165         Indicates that the newly allocated unbacked SymInts are being 
4166         discarded 
4167         """
4168         prev = self._ignore_fresh_unbacked_symbols_set(True)
4169         try:
4170             yield
4171         finally:
4172             self._ignore_fresh_unbacked_symbols_set(prev)
4173 
4174     @record_shapeenv_event()
4175     def freeze(self) -> None:
4176         """Freeze this ShapeEnv to stop accumulating guards 
4177  
4178         A frozen ShapeEnv will ignore any further guards generated on it and 
4179         only emit a warning which may lead to accuracy problems. 
4180         """
4181         self.frozen = True
4182 
4183     @record_shapeenv_event()
4184     def freeze_runtime_asserts(self) -> None:
4185         """Freeze this ShapeEnv to stop adding deferred runtime asserts. 
4186  
4187         We will error if you try to install a new runtime assert when it is 
4188         frozen.  This would indicate a lowering violation, or perhaps something 
4189         we know statically is already True but we are checking it again in a way 
4190         that is not clearly dischargeable. 
4191         """
4192         # self.prefer_deferred_runtime_asserts_over_guards = False
4193         self.runtime_asserts_frozen = True

4195     def _create_symbol_for_source(self, source: Source) -> Optional[sympy.Symbol]:
4196         if not self._translation_validation_enabled:
4197             return None
4198         srcname = source.name()
4199         if source not in self.source_to_symbol:
4200             self.source_to_symbol[srcname] = sympy.Symbol(srcname, integer=True)
4201         return self.source_to_symbol[srcname]
4202 
4203     def _add_z3var(self, symbol: sympy.Symbol, type: type) -> None:
4204         if self._translation_validation_enabled:
4205             self.validator.add_var(symbol, type)
4206 
4207     def _add_target_expr(self, expr: SympyBoolean) -> None:
4208         if self._translation_validation_enabled:
4209             self.validator.add_target_expr(expr)
4210 
4211     def _add_assertion(self, expr: SympyBoolean) -> None:
4212         if self._translation_validation_enabled:
4213             self.validator.add_assertion(expr)
4214 
4215     def _check_translation_validate(self) -> None:
4216         if self._translation_validation_enabled:
4217             self.validator.validate()

4219     @record_shapeenv_event()
4220     def _create_fx_call_function(
4221         self,
4222         op: Callable,
4223         args: tuple,
4224     ) -> tuple[Optional[torch.fx.Node], bool]:
4225         # Cache this tuple in order to avoid duplicated nodes.
4226         node_key = (op, args)
4227         # Flags whether the returned node was cached or not.
4228         fresh = False
4229 
4230         if self._translation_validation_enabled and node_key not in self.fx_node_cache:
4231             # Presence of None in the arguments implies that we should ignore this operation.
4232             if any(a is None for a in args):
4233                 # We check if we are not mixing SymNode that should not be ignored
4234                 # (fx_node is not None) with those that should (fx_node is None).
4235                 assert all(not isinstance(a, torch.fx.Node) for a in args)
4236                 return None, fresh
4237 
4238             fresh = True
4239 
4240             # If translation validation is enabled, all arguments must have its
4241             # own FX node.
4242             assert all(a is not None for a in args), (
4243                 f"missing arg in FX graph ({op.__name__}): {args}"
4244             )
4245             node = self.fx_node_cache[node_key] = self.graph.call_function(op, args)
4246             self.name_to_node[node.name] = node
4247 
4248         return self.fx_node_cache.get(node_key, None), fresh
4249 
4250     def _create_fx_placeholder_and_z3var(
4251         self,
4252         symbol: sympy.Symbol,
4253         type: type,
4254     ) -> Optional[torch.fx.Node]:
4255         if not self._translation_validation_enabled:
4256             return None
4257 
4258         node_key = (self.graph.placeholder, (symbol,))
4259 
4260         # Check if we haven't added this symbol already.
4261         # If so, skip the placeholder creation, as it
4262         # generates invalid Python code.
4263         if node_key not in self.fx_node_cache:
4264             # Add a Z3 variable according to 'type'.
4265             self._add_z3var(symbol, type)
4266             # Create the FX placeholder out of a mangled name.
4267             mangled_name = re.sub(
4268                 r"[^a-zA-Z0-9]", "_", re.sub(r"[()]", "", symbol.name)
4269             )
4270             node = self.fx_node_cache[node_key] = self.graph.placeholder(mangled_name)
4271             self.name_to_node[node.name] = node
4272             # Attach the 'symbol' to the placeholder so that we can retrieve
4273             # the Z3 variable later.
4274             node.meta["symbol"] = symbol
4275 
4276         return self.fx_node_cache[node_key]
4277 
4278     def _remove_fx_node(self, node: Optional[torch.fx.Node]) -> None:
4279         if self._translation_validation_enabled and node is not None:
4280             self.name_to_node.pop(node.name)
4281             self.graph.erase_node(node)
4282 
4283     def _add_fx_node_metadata(self, node: torch.fx.Node) -> None:
4284         from torch._dynamo.utils import get_current_node
4285 
4286         if self.should_record_events:
4287             node.meta[SHAPEENV_EVENT_KEY] = self._last_event_index()
4288             node.meta[CURRENT_NODE_KEY] = get_current_node()
4289 
4290     @staticmethod
4291     def _suppress_guards_tls() -> bool:
4292         return getattr(TLS, "suppress_guards", False)
4293 
4294     @record_shapeenv_event()
4295     def _suppress_guards_enter(self) -> None:
4296         if not hasattr(TLS, "suppress_guards_stack"):
4297             TLS.suppress_guards_stack = []
4298         old = self._suppress_guards_tls()
4299         TLS.suppress_guards_stack.append(old)
4300         TLS.suppress_guards = True
4301 
4302     @record_shapeenv_event()
4303     def _suppress_guards_exit(self) -> None:
4304         old = (
4305             TLS.suppress_guards_stack.pop()
4306             if len(TLS.suppress_guards_stack) > 0
4307             else False
4308         )
4309         TLS.suppress_guards = old
4310 
4311     def suppress_guards(self) -> _GeneratorContextManager[None]:
4312         """Context manager to ignore all guards generated inside"""
4313         return _suppress_guards(self)
4314 
4315     def _get_key(self) -> tuple[int, int, int, int]:
4316         """ 
4317         Defines the current "state" of the guards we've accumulated in this ShapeEnv. 
4318         Determines when we need to invalidate our cache 
4319         """
4320         return (
4321             len(self.replacements),
4322             len(self.divisible),
4323             self.num_deferred_runtime_asserts,
4324             len(self.unbacked_var_to_val),
4325         )
4326 
4327     def _update_version_counter(self) -> None:
4328         # if the change to shape env effects self.divisible set
4329         # _resimplify_floor_div_axioms.
4330         # This is used to trigger a resimplication of FloorDiv to CleanDivs
4331         # in implication inside the function resimplify_floor_div.
4332         if len(self.divisible) != self._prev_cache_key[1]:
4333             self._resimplify_floor_div_axioms = True
4334 
4335         # The shape environment is queried orders of magnitude more often than
4336         # it is changed, so we summarise the cache key into a linearly
4337         # increasing version counter which is cheaper to check in _lru_cache
4338 
4339         # Only update version counter if the state actually changed
4340         cur_key = self._get_key()
4341 
4342         if self._prev_cache_key != cur_key:
4343             self._prev_cache_key = cur_key
4344             self._version_counter += 1
4345 
4346     def _produce_dyn_sizes(
4347         self,
4348         ex_size: Sequence[IntLikeType],
4349         source: Source,
4350         symbolic_context: SymbolicContext,
4351     ) -> list[sympy.Expr]:
4352         return self._produce_dyn_sizes_from_int_tuple(
4353             tuple(ex_size), source, symbolic_context
4354         )
4355 
4356     def _produce_dyn_sizes_from_int_tuple(
4357         self,
4358         tensor_size: Sequence[IntLikeType],
4359         source: Source,
4360         symbolic_context: SymbolicContext,
4361     ) -> list[sympy.Expr]:
4362         assert all(not is_symbolic(val) for val in tensor_size), (
4363             f"Expect size to be a plain tuple of ints but got {tensor_size}"
4364         )
4365         from torch._dynamo.source import TensorProperty, TensorPropertySource
4366 
4367         _assert_symbol_context(symbolic_context)
4368         dynamic_dims = symbolic_context.dynamic_sizes  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
4369         constraint_dims = symbolic_context.constraint_sizes  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
4370         size = []
4371         for i, val in enumerate(tensor_size):
4372             sym = self.create_symbol(
4373                 val,
4374                 TensorPropertySource(source, TensorProperty.SIZE, i),
4375                 dynamic_dims[i],
4376                 constraint_dims[i],
4377                 do_not_specialize_zero_one=config.backed_size_oblivious,
4378                 symbolic_context=symbolic_context,
4379             )
4380             if (
4381                 isinstance(symbolic_context, StatelessSymbolicContext)
4382                 and symbolic_context.specialize_on
4383             ):
4384                 for specialization in symbolic_context.specialize_on[i]:
4385                     self.specializations.add(
4386                         Specialization(
4387                             TensorPropertySource(source, TensorProperty.SIZE, i),
4388                             specialization,
4389                         )
4390                     )
4391             if (
4392                 config.backed_size_oblivious
4393                 and isinstance(sym, sympy.Symbol)  # could be static
4394                 and symbol_is_type(sym, SymT.SIZE)
4395             ):
4396                 self.size_like.add(sym)
4397             size.append(sym)
4398         return size
4399 
4400     def create_symbolic_sizes_strides_storage_offset(
4401         self,
4402         ex: torch.Tensor,
4403         source: Source,
4404         *,
4405         symbolic_context: Optional[SymbolicContext] = None,
4406     ) -> tuple[
4407         tuple[IntLikeType, ...],
4408         tuple[IntLikeType, ...],
4409         IntLikeType,
4410     ]:
4411         """ 
4412         Returns a list of symbolic sizes and strides for the given tensor. 
4413         We try our best to express stride in terms of the sizes, so as to not 
4414         introduce new symbolic variables. 
4415         """
4416 
4417         ex_size = tuple(
4418             self._maybe_specialize_sym_int_with_hint(sz) for sz in ex.size()
4419         )
4420         ex_stride = tuple(
4421             self._maybe_specialize_sym_int_with_hint(sd) for sd in ex.stride()
4422         )
4423         ex_storage_offset = self._maybe_specialize_sym_int_with_hint(
4424             ex.storage_offset()
4425         )
4426 
4427         return self._create_symbolic_sizes_strides_storage_offset(
4428             ex_size,
4429             ex_stride,
4430             ex_storage_offset,
4431             [_is_dim_dynamic(ex, i) for i in range(ex.dim())],
4432             source,
4433             symbolic_context=symbolic_context,
4434         )
4435 
4436     # Dynamo may want to wrap FakeTensors with SymInt sizes up e.g. make_fx(opt_f(), tracing_mode="symbolic").
4437     # We create symbols in shape_env using the backed hints behind SymInt.
4438 
4439     # Case 1: when SymInt is backed, dynamo can proceed with FakeTensors that have concrete shape.
4440     # produce_guards will trigger specializations on the outer stuff
4441 
4442     # Case 2: when the SymInt is unbacked, we will throw an data dependent error in require_hint().
4443     #
4444     # It's probably good for now but it's important to note that this approach has implications for
4445     # the original shape_env when checking guards in different order.
4446 
4447     # Example:
4448     # ---------
4449     # Consider a function "opt_f" as shown below:
4450 
4451     # @torch.compile()
4452     # def opt_f(x: bool, y: Tensor):
4453     #   if x == True:
4454     #     return y + torch.randn([4])
4455     #   else:
4456     #     return y
4457     # Depending on the sequence of calls, we might install two different sets of guards:
4458 
4459     # 1. opt_f(False, y):
4460     #    - "x == False" (always works for any size y)
4461 
4462     # 2. opt_f(True, y):
4463     #    - Triggers recompilation and results in guards like:
4464     #      - "x == True and y.size(0) == 4"
4465     #      - (or "y.size(0) == 4 and x == True")
4466 
4467     # The order of checking the guards matters. In this specific example:
4468     # If True branch guard check precedes False branch and for True branch, y.size(0) check precedes x == True,
4469     # we may have an unnessary shape speciliazation for y.
4470     def _maybe_specialize_sym_int_with_hint(
4471         self, maybe_sym: IntLikeType
4472     ) -> IntLikeType:
4473         assert isinstance(maybe_sym, (int, torch.SymInt))
4474         if is_symbolic(maybe_sym):
4475             assert maybe_sym.node.shape_env is not self, (
4476                 "expect the symbol is created from an shape env other than current one."
4477             )
4478             return maybe_sym.node.require_hint()
4479         return maybe_sym
4480 
4481     @record_shapeenv_event()
4482     def _create_symbolic_sizes_strides_storage_offset(
4483         self,
4484         # NB: SymInt is allowed here due to nested int, normally you don't
4485         # actually pass true symbolic sizes to this function
4486         ex_size: Sequence[IntLikeType],
4487         ex_stride: Sequence[IntLikeType],
4488         ex_storage_offset: IntLikeType,
4489         is_dim_dynamic: Sequence[bool],
4490         source: Source,
4491         *,
4492         symbolic_context: Optional[SymbolicContext] = None,
4493     ) -> tuple[
4494         tuple[IntLikeType, ...],
4495         tuple[IntLikeType, ...],
4496         IntLikeType,
4497     ]:
4498         dim = len(ex_size)
4499 
4500         # Reimplement the legacy behavior
4501         if symbolic_context is None:
4502             constraint_sizes: list[DimConstraint] = [None] * dim
4503             constraint_strides: list[DimConstraint] = [None] * dim
4504             dynamic_dims = []
4505             dynamic_strides = []
4506             for i in range(dim):
4507                 # NB: This is encapsulation breaking!  Legacy behavior was
4508                 # bad.
4509                 if is_dim_dynamic[i]:
4510                     r = DimDynamic.DYNAMIC
4511                 elif self.assume_static_by_default:
4512                     r = DimDynamic.STATIC
4513                 else:
4514                     r = DimDynamic.DUCK
4515                 dynamic_dims.append(r)
4516                 dynamic_strides.append(r)
4517             dynamic_dims = [DimDynamic.DUCK] * dim
4518             dynamic_strides = [DimDynamic.INFER_STRIDE] * dim
4519             # symbolic_context is None - set one
4520             symbolic_context = StatelessSymbolicContext(
4521                 dynamic_sizes=dynamic_dims,
4522                 dynamic_strides=dynamic_strides,
4523                 constraint_sizes=constraint_sizes,
4524                 constraint_strides=constraint_strides,
4525             )
4526         # We got a StatelessSymbolicContext
4527         _assert_symbol_context(symbolic_context)
4528         constraint_sizes = symbolic_context.constraint_sizes  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
4529         constraint_strides = symbolic_context.constraint_strides  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
4530         dynamic_sizes = symbolic_context.dynamic_sizes  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
4531         dynamic_strides = symbolic_context.dynamic_strides  # type: ignore[attr-defined]
4532 
4533         # TODO: make this configurable from outside symbolic_context; we made a symbolic_context
4534         # decision here where if all sizes are static, we are going to
4535         # specialize all of the inner strides/offset too. We don't have to
4536         # do this, and arguably we should ALWAYS allow for dynamic offset,
4537         # this is cheap.
4538         # TODO: This should be DYNAMIC, using DUCK for BC
4539         dynamic_offset = (
4540             DimDynamic.STATIC
4541             if all(r == DimDynamic.STATIC for r in dynamic_sizes)
4542             else DimDynamic.DUCK
4543         )
4544         are_sizes_static = all(r == DimDynamic.STATIC for r in dynamic_sizes)
4545 
4546         assert len(dynamic_sizes) == dim, f"{len(dynamic_sizes)} != {dim}"
4547         assert len(dynamic_strides) == dim, f"{len(dynamic_sizes)} != {dim}"
4548         assert len(constraint_sizes) == dim
4549         assert len(constraint_strides) == dim
4550 
4551         from torch._dynamo.source import TensorProperty, TensorPropertySource
4552 
4553         size: list[sympy.Expr] = self._produce_dyn_sizes_from_int_tuple(
4554             ex_size, source, symbolic_context
4555         )
4556         stride = self._compute_symbolic_stride(
4557             source,
4558             size,
4559             ex_size,
4560             ex_stride,
4561             dynamic_strides,
4562             constraint_strides,
4563             are_sizes_static,
4564             symbolic_context,
4565         )
4566 
4567         sym_sizes = [
4568             self.create_symintnode(
4569                 sym,
4570                 hint=hint,
4571                 source=TensorPropertySource(source, TensorProperty.SIZE, i),
4572             )
4573             for i, (sym, hint) in enumerate(zip(size, ex_size))
4574         ]
4575         sym_stride = []
4576         for i, stride_expr in enumerate(stride):
4577             # NB: Don't duck size the stride; instead use the expression
4578             # we computed
4579             assert stride_expr is not None
4580             sym_stride.append(
4581                 self.create_symintnode(
4582                     stride_expr,
4583                     hint=ex_stride[i],
4584                     source=TensorPropertySource(source, TensorProperty.STRIDE, i),
4585                 )
4586             )
4587         sym_storage_offset = self.create_symintnode(
4588             self.create_symbol(
4589                 ex_storage_offset,
4590                 TensorPropertySource(source, TensorProperty.STORAGE_OFFSET),
4591                 dynamic_dim=dynamic_offset,
4592                 constraint_dim=None,
4593                 symbolic_context=symbolic_context,
4594             ),
4595             hint=ex_storage_offset,
4596             source=TensorPropertySource(source, TensorProperty.STORAGE_OFFSET),
4597         )
4598         return tuple(sym_sizes), tuple(sym_stride), sym_storage_offset
4599 
4600     def _compute_symbolic_stride(
4601         self,
4602         source: Source,
4603         size: Sequence[sympy.Expr],
4604         ex_size: Sequence[IntLikeType],
4605         ex_stride: Sequence[IntLikeType],
4606         dynamic_strides: Sequence[DimDynamic],
4607         constraint_strides: Sequence[
4608             Optional[Union[StrictMinMaxConstraint, RelaxedUnspecConstraint]]
4609         ],
4610         are_sizes_static: bool,
4611         symbolic_context: SymbolicContext,
4612     ) -> list[sympy.Expr]:
4613         from torch._dynamo.source import TensorProperty, TensorPropertySource
4614 
4615         stride: list[Optional[sympy.Expr]] = [None] * len(size)
4616         candidates: dict[IntLikeType, sympy.Expr] = {}
4617 
4618         # iterate over unbound strides in val ascending order with
4619         # index descending as a tie breaker since for cases like
4620         # [(1, 1), (1, 0)], we want to fill in the right most
4621         # stride first.
4622         val_list = [(val, -i) for i, val in enumerate(ex_stride)]
4623         val_list.sort(key=_nested_int_aware_sort)
4624 
4625         for val, neg_i in val_list:
4626             i = -neg_i
4627             contiguous_stride = (
4628                 i != len(ex_stride) - 1
4629                 and ex_stride[i] == ex_size[i + 1] * ex_stride[i + 1]
4630             )
4631             if val in (0, 1) and not contiguous_stride:
4632                 out_stride = sympy.Integer(val)
4633             else:
4634                 dynamic_stride = dynamic_strides[i]
4635                 if dynamic_stride == DimDynamic.INFER_STRIDE and val in candidates:
4636                     # Set stride to a candidate only for DimDynamic.INFER_STRIDE
4637                     out_stride = candidates[val]
4638                 else:
4639                     # Set INFER_STRIDE to STATIC or DUCK depending on sizes
4640                     dyn_stride = dynamic_stride
4641                     if dynamic_stride == DimDynamic.INFER_STRIDE:
4642                         dyn_stride = (
4643                             DimDynamic.STATIC if are_sizes_static else DimDynamic.DUCK
4644                         )
4645                     out_stride = self.create_symbol(
4646                         val,
4647                         TensorPropertySource(source, TensorProperty.STRIDE, i),
4648                         dynamic_dim=dyn_stride,
4649                         constraint_dim=constraint_strides[i],
4650                         symbolic_context=symbolic_context,
4651                     )
4652             stride[i] = out_stride
4653             candidates[ex_size[i] * val] = size[i] * out_stride
4654 
4655         assert all(x is not None for x in stride)
4656         return stride
4657 
4658     @record_shapeenv_event()
4659     def create_symintnode(
4660         self,
4661         sym: sympy.Expr,
4662         *,
4663         hint: Optional[int],
4664         source: Optional[Source] = None,
4665     ) -> IntLikeType:
4666         """Create a SymInt value from a symbolic expression 
4667  
4668         If you know what the current hint value of the SymInt to be created 
4669         is, pass it into hint.  Otherwise, pass None and we will make our best 
4670         guess 
4671  
4672         """
4673         if self._translation_validation_enabled and source is not None:
4674             # Create a new symbol for this source.
4675             symbol = self._create_symbol_for_source(source)
4676             assert symbol is not None
4677 
4678             # Create a new FX placeholder and Z3 variable for 'symbol'.
4679             fx_node = self._create_fx_placeholder_and_z3var(symbol, int)
4680 
4681             # Add an equality assertion for the newly created symbol and 'sym'.
4682             self._add_assertion(sympy.Eq(symbol, sym))
4683         else:
4684             fx_node = None
4685 
4686         out: IntLikeType
4687         if isinstance(sym, sympy.Integer):
4688             if hint is not None:
4689                 assert int(sym) == hint
4690             out = int(sym)
4691         else:
4692             # How can this occur? When we mark_unbacked, we end up with a real
4693             # tensor that has hints for all sizes, but we MUST NOT create a
4694             # SymNode with a hint, because we're hiding the hint from our eyes
4695             # with the unbacked Symbol.  And in fact, the hint compute may be
4696             # inconsistent with size oblivious tests.
4697             if free_unbacked_symbols(sym):
4698                 hint = None
4699             out = SymInt(SymNode(sym, self, int, hint, fx_node=fx_node))
4700         return out
4701 
4702     @record_shapeenv_event()
4703     def create_symfloatnode(
4704         self,
4705         sym: sympy.Expr,
4706         *,
4707         hint: Optional[int],
4708         source: Optional[Source] = None,
4709     ) -> FloatLikeType:
4710         """Create a SymFloat value from a symbolic expression"""
4711         if self._translation_validation_enabled and source is not None:
4712             # Create a new symbol for this source.
4713             symbol = self._create_symbol_for_source(source)
4714             assert symbol is not None
4715 
4716             # Create a new FX placeholder and Z3 variable for 'symbol'.
4717             fx_node = self._create_fx_placeholder_and_z3var(symbol, float)
4718 
4719             # Add an equality assertion for the newly created symbol and 'sym'.
4720             self._add_assertion(sympy.Eq(symbol, sym))
4721         else:
4722             fx_node = None
4723 
4724         out: FloatLikeType
4725         if isinstance(sym, sympy.Float):
4726             if hint is not None:
4727                 assert float(sym) == hint
4728             out = float(sym)
4729         else:
4730             # You could give this the same treatment as SymInt above if
4731             # you supported mark_unbacked on a float, but it's a kind of
4732             # strange thing to do though because floats don't get 0/1
4733             # specialization anyway
4734             if free_unbacked_symbols(sym):
4735                 assert hint is None, sym
4736             out = SymFloat(SymNode(sym, self, float, hint, fx_node=fx_node))
4737         return out
4738 
4739     @record_shapeenv_event()
4740     def create_unspecified_symint_and_symbol(
4741         self, value: int, source: Source, dynamic_dim: DimDynamic
4742     ) -> IntLikeType:
4743         """Create a SymInt wrapping a new unspecified symbol"""
4744         return self.create_symintnode(
4745             self.create_unspecified_symbol(
4746                 value,
4747                 source=source,
4748                 dynamic_dim=dynamic_dim,
4749             ),
4750             hint=value,
4751             source=source,
4752         )

4754     def create_symboolnode(self, sym: sympy.Expr) -> SymBool:
4755         """Create a SymBool object from a sympy boolean expression"""
4756         # This function is only being used in serialization, so we do not track it
4757         # for validation.
4758         return SymBool(SymNode(sym, self, bool, None))

4760     def _log_create_unbacked_symbol(
4761         self,
4762         prefix: str,
4763         symbol: sympy.Symbol,
4764         vr: ValueRanges,
4765         source: Optional[Source] = None,
4766         sym_node: Optional[SymNode] = None,
4767     ) -> None:
4768         is_debug = config.extended_debug_create_symbol is not None and str(
4769             symbol
4770         ) in config.extended_debug_create_symbol.split(",")
4771         sloc: Union[str, SLoc]
4772         if source is None:
4773             sloc, maybe_extra_debug = self._get_stack_summary(is_debug)
4774         else:
4775             sloc, maybe_extra_debug = source.name(), ""
4776         log.info(
4777             "%s %s [%s, %s] %s%s",
4778             prefix,
4779             symbol,
4780             vr.lower,
4781             vr.upper,
4782             sloc,
4783             maybe_extra_debug,
4784             stack_info=is_debug,
4785         )
4786         trace_structured(
4787             "create_unbacked_symbol",
4788             metadata_fn=lambda: {
4789                 "symbol": str(symbol),
4790                 "node_id": id(sym_node),
4791                 "vr": f"[{vr.lower}, {vr.upper}]",
4792                 "user_stack": structured.get_user_stack(3),
4793                 "stack": structured.get_framework_stack(),
4794             },
4795         )

4797     @record_shapeenv_event()
4798     def create_unbacked_symfloat(self) -> SymFloat:
4799         """Create a symbolic float without a hint value"""
4800         symbol: sympy.Symbol = make_symbol(
4801             SymT.UNBACKED_FLOAT, next(self.unbacked_symfloat_counter)
4802         )
4803         self.counter["create_unbacked_symbol"] += 1
4804         if not self._ignore_fresh_unbacked_symbols_tls():
4805             self.pending_fresh_unbacked_symbols.append(symbol)
4806         self.var_to_stack[symbol] = CapturedTraceback.extract(skip=1)
4807         vr = self.var_to_range[symbol] = ValueRanges.unknown()
4808         assert vr.is_float
4809         sloc = self._get_sloc()
4810         self.var_to_range_sloc[symbol] = ValueRangesSLoc(sloc, sloc)
4811 
4812         # Create a new FX placeholder and Z3 variable for 'symbol'.
4813         fx_node = self._create_fx_placeholder_and_z3var(symbol, float)
4814 
4815         sym_node = SymNode(symbol, self, float, None, fx_node=fx_node)
4816         self._log_create_unbacked_symbol(
4817             "create_unbacked_symfloat", symbol, vr, sym_node=sym_node
4818         )
4819 
4820         return SymFloat(sym_node)
4821 
4822     @record_shapeenv_event()
4823     def create_unbacked_symint(self, source: Optional[Source] = None) -> SymInt:
4824         """Create a symbolic integer without a hint value"""
4825         symbol: sympy.Symbol = make_symbol(
4826             SymT.UNBACKED_INT, next(self.unbacked_symint_counter), integer=True
4827         )
4828         if not self._ignore_fresh_unbacked_symbols_tls():
4829             self.pending_fresh_unbacked_symbols.append(symbol)
4830         self.counter["create_unbacked_symbol"] += 1
4831         self.var_to_stack[symbol] = CapturedTraceback.extract(skip=1)
4832         vr = self.var_to_range[symbol] = self._default_unspecified_value_range()
4833         assert vr.is_int
4834         sloc = self._get_sloc()
4835         self.var_to_range_sloc[symbol] = ValueRangesSLoc(sloc, sloc)
4836 
4837         # Create a new FX placeholder and Z3 variable for 'symbol'.
4838         fx_node = self._create_fx_placeholder_and_z3var(symbol, int)
4839 
4840         sym_node = SymNode(symbol, self, int, None, fx_node=fx_node)
4841         self._log_create_unbacked_symbol(
4842             "create_unbacked_symint", symbol, vr, source, sym_node=sym_node
4843         )
4844 
4845         return SymInt(sym_node)

4847     def is_unbacked_symint(self, symbol: sympy.Symbol) -> bool:
4848         """Check if a sympy symbol matches the naming convention for unbacked symbols"""
4849         return symbol_is_type(symbol, SymT.UNBACKED_INT)

4851     @record_shapeenv_event()
4852     def create_unbacked_symbool(self) -> SymBool:
4853         """Create a symbolic boolean without a hint value"""
4854         symbol: sympy.Symbol = make_symbol(
4855             SymT.UNBACKED_INT, next(self.unbacked_symint_counter), integer=True
4856         )
4857         if not self._ignore_fresh_unbacked_symbols_tls():
4858             self.pending_fresh_unbacked_symbols.append(symbol)
4859         self.counter["create_unbacked_symbol"] += 1
4860         self.var_to_stack[symbol] = CapturedTraceback.extract(skip=1)
4861         vr = self.var_to_range[symbol] = ValueRanges(0, 1)
4862         assert vr.is_int
4863         sloc = self._get_sloc("default value range for unbacked SymBool")
4864         self.var_to_range_sloc[symbol] = ValueRangesSLoc(sloc, sloc)
4865 
4866         # Create a new FX placeholder and Z3 variable for 'symbol'.
4867         fx_node = self._create_fx_placeholder_and_z3var(symbol, bool)
4868 
4869         sym_node = SymNode(sympy.Eq(symbol, 1), self, bool, None, fx_node=fx_node)
4870         self._log_create_unbacked_symbol(
4871             "create_unbacked_symbool", symbol, vr, sym_node=sym_node
4872         )
4873 
4874         return SymBool(sym_node)

4876     @record_shapeenv_event()
4877     def create_unspecified_symbol(
4878         self,
4879         val: Union[int, SymInt, float, SymFloat],
4880         source: Source,
4881         dynamic_dim: DimDynamic = DimDynamic.DUCK,
4882         constraint_dim: DimConstraint = None,  # NB: includes None
4883         symbolic_context: Optional[StatelessSymbolicContext] = None,
4884     ) -> sympy.Expr:
4885         """ 
4886         Create a symbol with an unspecified value 
4887  
4888         Compared to standard symbols we do not assume the value is positive, 
4889         nor do we specialze on zero or one values. 
4890         """
4891         # 'positive' is None for unspecified symbols, since we can't
4892         # assume that it will be neither positive nor negative.
4893 
4894         # We don't want to specialize zero one val for unspecified symbol
4895         # so that we can always get a new symbol despite val.
4896         return self.create_symbol(
4897             val,
4898             source,
4899             dynamic_dim,
4900             constraint_dim,
4901             positive=None,
4902             do_not_specialize_zero_one=True,
4903             symbolic_context=symbolic_context,
4904         )
4905 
4906     @record_shapeenv_event()
4907     def create_symbol(
4908         self,
4909         val: int,
4910         source: Source,
4911         dynamic_dim: DimDynamic = DimDynamic.DUCK,
4912         constraint_dim: DimConstraint = None,  # NB: includes None
4913         positive: Optional[bool] = True,
4914         do_not_specialize_zero_one: bool = False,
4915         symbolic_context: Optional[StatelessSymbolicContext] = None,
4916     ) -> sympy.Expr:
4917         """Create a new symbol which is tracked by this ShapeEnv"""
4918         # check if constraint_dim is actually static integer
4919         if (
4920             isinstance(constraint_dim, StrictMinMaxConstraint)
4921             and constraint_dim.vr.lower == constraint_dim.vr.upper
4922         ):
4923             dynamic_dim = DimDynamic.STATIC
4924             if constraint_dim.vr.lower != val:
4925                 raise ConstraintViolationError(
4926                     f"Static shape constraint of {constraint_dim.vr.lower} does not match input size of {val}, "
4927                     f"for {source.name()}"
4928                 )
4929             if symbolic_context:
4930                 from torch._dynamo.source import TensorPropertySource
4931 
4932                 assert isinstance(source, TensorPropertySource)
4933                 # TODO: storage_offset handling?
4934                 assert source.idx is not None
4935                 symbolic_context.dynamic_sizes[source.idx] = dynamic_dim
4936                 symbolic_context.constraint_sizes[source.idx] = None
4937             constraint_dim = None
4938 
4939         # see note [Tensor Fakification and Symbol Caching]
4940         source_name = source.name()
4941         if (
4942             isinstance(symbolic_context, StatefulSymbolicContext)
4943             and id(self) not in symbolic_context.shape_env_to_source_to_symbol_cache
4944         ):
4945             symbolic_context.shape_env_to_source_to_symbol_cache[id(self)] = {}
4946 
4947         if (
4948             isinstance(symbolic_context, StatefulSymbolicContext)
4949             and source_name
4950             and (
4951                 source_name
4952                 in symbolic_context.shape_env_to_source_to_symbol_cache[id(self)]
4953             )
4954         ):
4955             return symbolic_context.shape_env_to_source_to_symbol_cache[id(self)][
4956                 source_name
4957             ]
4958 
4959         if dynamic_dim in (DimDynamic.SIZE_LIKE_UNBACKED, DimDynamic.OBLIVIOUS_SIZE):
4960             out = self.create_unbacked_symint(source).node.expr
4961             self._constrain_range_for_size(out)
4962             if isinstance(symbolic_context, StatefulSymbolicContext) and source_name:
4963                 symbolic_context.shape_env_to_source_to_symbol_cache[id(self)][
4964                     source_name
4965                 ] = out
4966             if dynamic_dim is DimDynamic.OBLIVIOUS_SIZE:
4967                 self.oblivious_var_to_val[out] = val
4968             return out
4969 
4970         if do_not_specialize_zero_one:
4971             specialize_zero_one = False
4972         else:
4973             specialize_zero_one = self.specialize_zero_one
4974 
4975         assert isinstance(source, Source), f"{type(source)} {source}"
4976         assert not (positive and val < 0), f"positive set for negative value: {val}"
4977         # It's always sound to allocate a symbol as DYNAMIC.  If the user
4978         # constrained the symbol, force the symbolic_context to DYNAMIC, because our
4979         # constraint code will do weird stuff if, e.g., it's duck shaped
4980         if constraint_dim is not None:
4981             dynamic_dim = DimDynamic.DYNAMIC
4982 
4983         if dynamic_dim is DimDynamic.STATIC:
4984             out = sympy.Integer(val)
4985             if isinstance(symbolic_context, StatefulSymbolicContext) and source_name:
4986                 symbolic_context.shape_env_to_source_to_symbol_cache[id(self)][
4987                     source_name
4988                 ] = out
4989             return out
4990 
4991         elif dynamic_dim is DimDynamic.DUCK:
4992             # duck_shape can be used to globally turn off duck shaping, even
4993             # if it was requested
4994             duck = self.duck_shape
4995         elif dynamic_dim is DimDynamic.DYNAMIC:
4996             duck = False
4997         else:
4998             raise AssertionError(f"unhandled dynamic_dim {dynamic_dim}")
4999 
5000         sloc = self._get_sloc()
5001 
5002         if val in (0, 1) and specialize_zero_one:
5003             if val == 0:
5004                 return sympy.S.Zero
5005             else:
5006                 return sympy.S.One
5007         elif not duck or val not in self.val_to_var:
5008             # If we're not duck shaping, we always create a new symbol
5009             # Even if we're duck shaping, if we haven't seen this particular
5010             # value before, we also create a new symbol
5011             symbol_id = self._generate_unique_id(source.name())
5012             if type(val) is int or is_nested_int(val):
5013                 sympy_expr = make_symbol(
5014                     SymT.SIZE, symbol_id, positive=positive, integer=True
5015                 )
5016             else:
5017                 sympy_expr = make_symbol(
5018                     SymT.FLOAT, symbol_id, positive=positive, real=True
5019                 )
5020             self.source_to_var[source_name] = sympy_expr
5021             # We always associate vars to vals
5022             if isinstance(val, int):
5023                 self.var_to_val[sympy_expr] = sympy.Integer(val)
5024             elif isinstance(val, float):
5025                 self.var_to_val[sympy_expr] = sympy.Float(val)
5026             else:
5027                 # Only used for jagged layout nested tensors
5028                 self.var_to_val[sympy_expr] = SingletonInt(
5029                     val.node.nested_int(), coeff=val.node.nested_int_coeff()
5030                 )
5031 
5032             # Do the appending later, because we always want to populate this
5033             self.var_to_sources[sympy_expr] = []
5034             # Create a Z3 variable for the new symbol.
5035             self._add_z3var(sympy_expr, int)
5036 
5037             if duck:
5038                 # Make sure to reuse this symbol for subsequent duck shaping
5039                 self.val_to_var[val] = sympy_expr
5040 
5041             if isinstance(val, int):
5042                 if positive:
5043                     # Add assertions for the newly created symbols
5044                     self._add_assertion(sympy_expr > 1)
5045 
5046                     # Apply default range, which assumes not zero-one
5047                     self.var_to_range[sympy_expr] = self._default_value_range(
5048                         do_not_specialize_zero_one
5049                     )
5050                     self.var_to_range_sloc[sympy_expr] = ValueRangesSLoc(
5051                         self._get_sloc(
5052                             "user code shown is first use of this value--the guard itself is not "
5053                             "due user code but due to 0/1 specialization in the framework; to "
5054                             "avoid specialization try torch._dynamo.mark_unbacked(tensor, dim)"
5055                             if self.specialize_zero_one
5056                             else None
5057                         ),
5058                         sloc,
5059                     )
5060                 else:
5061                     self.var_to_range[sympy_expr] = (
5062                         self._default_unspecified_value_range()
5063                     )
5064                     self.var_to_range_sloc[sympy_expr] = ValueRangesSLoc(sloc, sloc)
5065 
5066                 # Small performance optimization: if we have a min-max constraint,
5067                 # we can proactively narrow to that range
5068                 if isinstance(constraint_dim, StrictMinMaxConstraint):
5069                     assert not duck
5070                     self._update_var_to_range(
5071                         sympy_expr, constraint_dim.vr, is_constraint=True
5072                     )
5073 
5074                 vr = self.var_to_range[sympy_expr]
5075                 assert vr.is_int
5076 
5077                 if val not in vr:
5078                     raise ConstraintViolationError(
5079                         f"{val} not in range [{vr.lower}, {vr.upper}]"
5080                     )
5081 
5082                 range_str = f"[{vr.lower}, {vr.upper}]"
5083             elif isinstance(val, float):
5084                 self.var_to_range[sympy_expr] = vr = ValueRanges(-sympy.oo, sympy.oo)
5085                 self.var_to_range_sloc[sympy_expr] = ValueRangesSLoc(sloc, sloc)
5086                 range_str = f"[{vr.lower}, {vr.upper}]"
5087                 assert vr.is_float
5088             else:
5089                 # Skip var_range logic for SingletonInt
5090                 # Only used for jagged layout nested tensors
5091                 range_str = ""
5092 
5093             r = sympy_expr
5094 
5095             is_debug = config.extended_debug_create_symbol is not None and str(
5096                 sympy_expr
5097             ) in config.extended_debug_create_symbol.split(",")
5098             maybe_more_info = ""
5099             if not is_debug and os.getenv("TORCHDYNAMO_EXTENDED_ADVICE", "1") not in (
5100                 "0",
5101                 "",
5102             ):
5103                 maybe_more_info = (
5104                     ", for more info run with "
5105                     f'TORCHDYNAMO_EXTENDED_DEBUG_CREATE_SYMBOL="{sympy_expr}" '
5106                     "or to suppress this message run with "
5107                     'TORCHDYNAMO_EXTENDED_ADVICE="0"'
5108                 )
5109             sloc, maybe_extra_debug = self._get_stack_summary(is_debug)
5110             self.log.info(
5111                 "create_symbol %s = %s for %s %s %s%s%s",
5112                 sympy_expr,
5113                 val,
5114                 source.name(),
5115                 range_str,
5116                 sloc,
5117                 maybe_more_info,
5118                 maybe_extra_debug,
5119                 stack_info=is_debug,
5120             )
5121             trace_structured(
5122                 "create_symbol",
5123                 metadata_fn=lambda: {
5124                     "symbol": str(sympy_expr),
5125                     "val": repr(val),
5126                     "vr": range_str,
5127                     "source": source.name(),
5128                     "user_stack": structured.from_traceback(
5129                         TracingContext.extract_stack()
5130                     ),
5131                     "stack": structured.from_traceback(
5132                         CapturedTraceback.extract(skip=1).summary()
5133                     ),
5134                 },
5135             )
5136 
5137             self.counter["create_symbol"] += 1
5138         else:
5139             # This implements duck-shaping: input sizes that match are assigned
5140             # the same symint
5141             r = self.val_to_var[val]
5142             self.source_to_var[source_name] = r
5143             self.log.debug("create_symbol %s duck sized %s", r, source.name())
5144 
5145         if isinstance(r, sympy.Symbol):
5146             r_sources = self.var_to_sources[r]
5147             r_sources.append(source)
5148             if not source.is_ephemeral() and r_sources[0].is_ephemeral():
5149                 # prefer non-ephemeral source first since it may be guarded on later
5150                 r_sources[0], r_sources[-1] = r_sources[-1], r_sources[0]
5151 
5152             # This ensures we get zeros in symbol_guard_counts, which makes
5153             # some queries simpler (since we will accumulate mass on 0 this
5154             # way)
5155             self.symbol_guard_counter[r] = 0
5156 
5157         if isinstance(symbolic_context, StatefulSymbolicContext) and source_name:
5158             symbolic_context.shape_env_to_source_to_symbol_cache[id(self)][
5159                 source_name
5160             ] = r
5161         return r
5162 
5163     def add_var_to_val(self, expr: sympy.Symbol, val: int) -> None:
5164         """Adds a new symbol to the symbolic environment."""
5165         log.debug("add_var_to_val %s %s", expr, val, stack_info=True)
5166         assert expr not in self.var_to_val, f"{expr} already exists"
5167         self.var_to_val[expr] = sympy.Integer(val)
5168 
5169     def _debug_name(self, source: Source) -> str:
5170         src_name = source.name()
5171         return self.source_name_to_debug_name.get(src_name, src_name)
5172 
5173     def _render_range_for_constraint_violation(
5174         self, source: Source, c: Union[StrictMinMaxConstraint, RelaxedUnspecConstraint]
5175     ) -> str:
5176         if isinstance(c, StrictMinMaxConstraint):
5177             lower, upper = c.vr.lower, c.vr.upper
5178             default = self._default_value_range()
5179             if lower <= default.lower:
5180                 lower = None
5181             if upper >= default.upper:
5182                 upper = None
5183             c_render = (
5184                 f"{self._debug_name(source)} = {source.name()} in the specified range"
5185             )
5186             if lower is not None and upper is not None:
5187                 c_render += f" {lower} <= {self._debug_name(source)} <= {upper}"
5188             elif lower is None and upper is not None:
5189                 c_render += f" {self._debug_name(source)} <= {upper}"
5190             elif lower is not None and upper is None:
5191                 c_render += f" {lower} <= {self._debug_name(source)}"
5192             return c_render
5193         return c.render(source)
5194 
5195     def produce_guards(self, *args: Any, **kwargs: Any) -> list[str]:
5196         """ 
5197         Like produce_guards_verbose, but only returns the non-verbose python guard expressions 
5198         (no verbose guards produced.) 
5199         """
5200         return self.produce_guards_verbose(*args, **kwargs, langs=("python",))[0].exprs
5201 
5202     def produce_guards_verbose(
5203         self,
5204         placeholders: Sequence[FakeTensor],
5205         sources: Sequence[Source],
5206         source_ref: Callable[[Source], str] = lambda n: n.name(),
5207         *,
5208         guards: Optional[list[ShapeGuard]] = None,
5209         input_contexts: Optional[DimList[SymbolicContext]] = None,
5210         # Encodes user-specified input shape equations of the form s = s' and s = fn(s').
5211         # (See docs on EqualityConstraint for details of the encoding.)
5212         equalities_inputs: Optional[EqualityConstraint] = None,
5213         _simplified: bool = False,
5214         # Indicates if we should produce guards for known static values.
5215         ignore_static: bool = True,
5216         langs: tuple[str, ...] = ("python", "verbose_python"),
5217     ) -> list[_ShapeGuardsHelper]:
5218         """ 
5219         Generates a list of guards strings which, when evaluated in a context that 
5220         defines tensors for all the sources, returns True or False depending 
5221         on if the guards in the list evaluated to True or not.  Primarily used by Dynamo, 
5222         but this is also helpful for manual testing of guards (see 
5223         evaluate_guards_for_args) 
5224  
5225         For convenience in testing, a source is allowed to be a str, 
5226         in which case we will assume it is a LocalSource 
5227  
5228         simplified lets you omit duck sizing, equality and 0/1 guards. 
5229         This is useful for testing when you don't care about the boilerplate 
5230         guards, and it may be helpful for user output too (be careful though; 
5231         some equality guards are nontrivial!  It would be nice to get simplified 
5232         output to print them too).  It's private because it's not 
5233         intended for normal use 
5234  
5235         Returns guards in python and python with verbose comments (verbose) by 
5236         default. 
5237         """
5238         self.log.info("produce_guards")
5239 
5240         # Check if we get to the same ShapeEnv state by replaying the recorded events.
5241         # This will create a new ShapeEnv instance, and call all recorded function
5242         # calls on this new instance. Finally, it will check whether this new instance
5243         # has equal state.
5244         #
5245         # It's important that we do it in the begining of this function, since it modifies
5246         # self.dim_constraints through its execution. Changes that happen in this method
5247         # aren't interesting, since this is the function call we wish to reproduce at the
